How to Install UModeler X Basic
1. Purchase the UModeler X Plus version from the Unity Asset Store.
3. Open the Unity Editor and go to Window > Package Manager from the top menu. Download and import the UModeler Hub from the UModeler X Plus package.
4. After downloading, click the UModeler Hub icon that appears at the top center of the Scene to open the window.
5. Click Create a New Account at the bottom.
6. Click the Sign up with Email and Password button, enter the required information such as your email and password, agree to the terms, and then click the Create a UModeler ID button.
7. A verification email will be sent. Log in to your email, check the verification email, and complete the verification process.
8. Click the Later button to exit the "Unlock your UModeler X Plus" page.
9. The Install button for UModeler X Basic will be activated. Click it to proceed with the installation.

How to Install UModeler X Plus
1. Purchase the UModeler X Plus version from the Unity Asset Store.
3. Open the Unity Editor and go to Window > Package Manager from the top menu. Download and import the UModeler Hub from the UModeler X Plus package.
4. After downloading, click the UModeler Hub icon that appears at the top center of the Scene to open the window.

The tutorial course for beginners in UModeler X has been newly strengthened, making it easy for anyone to enter the world of 3D modeling. Now, after learning the basics of modeling, rigging, and painting, you can proceed with practice-like exercises through low poly modeling. The newly added 'Lowpoly Table and Chair' and 'Lowpoly Tower' tutorial videos will be an excellent next step for those who have completed the basic education. Beginners are recommended to gradually learn the various features of UModeler X according to the tutorial course below. Each tutorial can be easily accessed through the provided links. Basic Tutorials Learn the basics of modeling, rigging, and painting. You can master the basics of UV editing. Link: Basic Tutorials Low Poly Tutorials Start with a simple table and chair and move on to towers and buildings. A low poly student room production tutorial will also be added soon. Link: Low Poly Tutorials Synty Studios and Mixamo Apply animations to your finished models. Link: Synty Studios and Mixamo This systematic tutorial course is designed to allow users who are new to UModeler X to learn step-by-step, from the basics to practical application. This tutorial will be a good guide on your journey to creating your own creations.
documents.s: Enhancements to the UModeler X Tutorial Courses for Beginners

documents.t: The UModeler X team, led by lead developer Kim Se-yong, conducted an innovative internal project called 'VR BlackSmith' to deeply explore the potential of the release version. This project aimed to integrate ancient blacksmith techniques into a modern VR environment. It was about implementing the traditional method of forging iron and making tools in a VR setting using UModeler X's advanced modeling technology. The project was carried out by dedicating 20% of Kim Se-yong's working hours from January to March. During this time, the focus was on meticulously testing and improving the modeling functionality of UModeler X and the runtime performance of the Boolean tool. These efforts confirmed that UModeler X could perform excellently in real-time environments. During the development process, the flexibility and powerful modeling capabilities of UModeler X were deeply explored for VR content creation. As a result, the 'VR BlackSmith' project successfully developed a prototype that allows users to experience blacksmith techniques and create tools within the VR environment using UModeler X's features. The project's achievements, despite being a prototype version, are demonstrated in a demo video, showcasing the core functionalities of UModeler X and proving its potential. The experiences and insights gained from this project will have a significant impact on the future development direction of UModeler X.

The updates to UModeler X over the last month have focused on improvements to modeling and painting modes, as well as performance enhancements for the UV editor and 3D painting. Version 0.19.6 addressed GPU crash issues, and versions 0.19.8 and 0.19.9 fixed various bugs to enhance the usability of modeling tools. Notably, the functionality of the bevel tool and slice cut tool was improved, and the accuracy of Boolean operations was enhanced, significantly improving the user experience. Additionally, issues with shortcuts in rigging and painting modes were resolved, increasing stability. For more detailed update information, please refer to UModeler X's release notes. UModeler X is moving towards a more stable version based on issues reported by you through the UModeler Discord server and email.
documents.s: UModeler X Updates Over the Last Month

documents.t: Hello, I’m Jaesik Hwang, CEO and Team Manager of UModeler. Time flies, and another month has passed quickly. As always, I'm here to share various UModeler updates from the past month.
documents.s: Unite 2024 Sponsorship and UModeler X Plus Release News

documents.t: UModeler is sponsoring the upcoming Unite 2024 event, which will be held from September 18th to 20th, 2024. We will also have a booth where you can learn about the latest updates on UModeler X. If you are in Barcelona, please drop by and say hello. If you have any questions about UModeler X or are interested in exploring new business opportunities with us, feel free to contact us in advance at Contact.Support@umodeler.com.

Coinciding with the Unite event, the early bird version of UModeler X Plus will be released. For about two weeks, you can get UModeler X Plus at a whopping 75% discount off the official November release price of $199. We also offer a special upgrade option for existing UModeler users. The upgrade cost is also discounted during the early bird period, so don’t miss out on this great opportunity.

The schedule for adding UModeler features and more to UModeler X Plus is as follows: September 2024 SketchUp Style Modeling Beta PushPull Tool Beta .OBJ, .STL, and .PLY Exporters Array Modifier and Tool October 2024 Normal Painting November 2024 Hotspot Texturing Tool SketchUp Style Modeling Full Version PushPull Tool Full Version Follow Tool Multi UV Channels Editing UModeler X Plus builds on the strong foundation of UModeler X Beta by adding essential UModeler features like SketchUp Style Modeling, Hotspot Texturing, Clone (Array) Tool, Follow Tool, Export Tool and Normal Painting allowing you to leverage all of UModeler’s powerful capabilities. With the official release of the Plus version in November, we’re also planning to launch Pro and Team licenses in the first quarter of next year. We’ll keep you updated on the progress.

documents.t: During the August Summer Sale, Korea’s famous Unity developer and YouTuber Golden Metal introduced UModeler with a fantastic video. You’ll find plenty of inspiration from watching him use UModeler at the start of the video.

After the 0.19.0 update in February, we’re excited to announce the 0.20.0 update, bringing new features for the first time in six months. This major update introduces the Face Color Tool and UV Param Tool, which were previously available in UModeler. Additionally, the Face Normal Tool, allowing you to edit the normal direction of faces, has been added in version 0.20.4.
This tool allows you to apply the desired color to selected faces. It is very useful when assigning colors or properties using RGBA values at the face level. Face Color Tool Go to Documentation
This tool allows you to transform UVs of unwrapped faces using properties like Shift, Rotate, and Scale. UV Param Tool Go to Documentation

This tool allows you to change the normal direction of selected faces. The manual page will be added soon. That’s all for this update. After returning from Unite 2024, I’ll bring you more exciting news next month.

Hello everyone! I'm very happy to introduce our second blog post. Today, we'll talk about the major updates made over the last two months, the newly added painting mode guide, and the backlog we are working on to make UModeler X even more stable.
documents.s: The Latest UModeler X Updates - What's New in January and February 2024

documents.t: Several useful features were added in January and February this year. Take a look, and if you're still using an older version of UModeler X, I hope you take this opportunity to update to the latest version.
documents.s: Major Updates for January and February 2024

documents.t: You can easily measure the distance between selected vertices and the length of edges.

he Height Snap feature has been added, allowing elements to be aligned based on the direction of movement and the position of the cursor. Additionally, Unity's Grid/Incremental snap functionality has been integrated into the basic shape tools. This improves accuracy and ease of use.
With the new Slice Cut tool, you can easily slice meshes by creating a virtual plane that matches the camera direction.
In UModeler X, you can assign shortcuts for all tools using Unity's shortcut manager.
With the new Decimate modifier, you can reduce the number of polygons in a mesh to efficiently optimize the model.

Check your UModeler X usage status with the new Commentary feature. It provides information on the tools you are using, mouse/keyboard inputs, and Undo/Redo actions. In addition to these feature additions, many improvements have been made. For more update news, please refer to the UModeler Discord channel.

A guide document for users starting with the painting mode has been added to the manual page. It's a very convenient feature that allows you to create or modify textures directly on 3D models. This guide provides useful information on how to start painting mode and how to use textures created in this mode.

Based on your feedback, we are working hard to update UModeler X every week. The backlog items scheduled to be addressed in the next 2-3 weeks are as follows. Performance issues when navigating the camera with the mouse in edit mode. Addition of a feature to reset properties in the LoopCut tool. Problems with selecting hidden polygons. Rendering issues when a disabled UModelerXEditableMesh component is reactivated. Unity freezing when saving the scene. Hierarchy problems occurring when umodelerizing multiple meshes. Improvement of painting brush speed.

We hope your 3D modeling experience improves with UModeler X, and we will always listen to your valuable feedback. Your interest and support are the driving forces behind the development of UModeler X. Please continue to support us.

Hello! I'm very excited to start a blog like this. I was thinking about what to write for my first blog post, and I decided it would be interesting to talk about why we started developing UModeler X, the process we went through, and how we plan to develop it further, as this is something we haven't had many chances to discuss. The reason I started developing UModeler X while the existing UModeler was receiving a lot of love from Unity developers is as follows: To allow for smooth editing of high-poly 3D data within the Unity editor. To integrate all functions needed for 3D data creation, including modeling, rigging, painting, and sculpting, so that games can be made 100% within Unity. To lay the groundwork for runtime solution development as well as editor solutions, aiming to develop new products for more 3D creators outside of Unity. To allow creators to make various contents such as 3D worlds, games, items, and characters with UModeler X, and to support more creators' creative activities with the results produced from here.

UModeler X began its full-scale development in mid-2020, facing various technical and planning challenges. We overcame these challenges one by one to reach its current form. I will briefly introduce the development process.

In 2020, the initial development focused on implementing an architecture that could quickly update the connectivity information between the elements of a mesh, such as vertices, edges, and faces. Additionally, we concentrated on ensuring that the visualization, selection, and movement of these mesh elements could be handled cleanly and swiftly. The BMesh architecture from Blender provided significant help in implementing this architecture. To verify performance, we conducted basic modeling tests such as element selection and movement using an 800,000 polygon Stanford Dragon mesh. The results confirmed that UModeler X could adequately edit high-poly models within Unity. In addition to this, we introduced a command-based modular approach to increase work efficiency and significantly reduce the data size needed for Undo/Redo operations. We also added the ability to modify the original mesh (Source Mesh) without altering it by introducing modifiers (Modifier). The initial implementation of the Mirror, Subdivide, FFD, Shell, and Push modifiers has made modeling much easier and more efficient. We adopted the OpenSubdiv library to implement a subdivision (Subdivision) tool that directly converts low-quality, low-poly 3D data into high-quality, high-poly 3D data.

We introduced the MVVM(Model-View-ViewModel) pattern to separate rendering, data, and actual implementation. Additionally, we upgraded the UI design to make it more sophisticated. We developed a solution that utilizes the GPU to select vertices, edges, and faces of high-poly meshes with high performance. We implemented various modeling-related features belonging to basic shapes (Primitive Shapes), Add, Remove, and Surface groups on top of the new architecture. We also implemented a built-in UV editor to enable UV unwrapping and editing. In the summer of 2021, we were able to create high-end 3D models that the original UModeler could not achieve, fully utilizing the features of UModeler X implemented up to that point. In UV editing, a new unwrapping feature using the LSCM (Least Squares Conformal Maps) algorithm was added, allowing complex meshes to be unfolded into 2D UV coordinates with minimal distortion by following the seams. We finally implemented rigging for character animation. Now, not only can you create a skeleton structure, but you can also import and use an existing skeleton directly. Additionally, we implemented the Weight Transfer feature, which calculates weights based on the weights of another mesh. By fully utilizing the modeling features and rigging implemented up to that point, we were able to successfully create character items for the Zepeto metaverse, thereby verifying the performance of UModeler X.

We continuously verified the capabilities of UModeler X by creating a demo that combined a cute character with a 2.5D proportion, made using UModeler X, with a background created using UModeler. Developed a 3D painting mode that allows direct coloring on 3D models with a brush. This supports layers like Photoshop, and each layer can have Paint, Fill, and Sticker properties. 2D painting is also supported, making it possible to create textures in Unity, which was previously cumbersome. 3D Painting Prototype First Version of 3D Painting Conducted more than three alpha tests targeting students learning Unity. Through this, we were able to receive a wide range of feedback and enhance the completeness of UModeler X. In 2022, a lot of time and effort were invested in adding new features, creating a stable and scalable system, and addressing technical debt. As a result, the existing command system, prefab, and tool usage workflows were significantly improved. Continuous testing led to the identification and resolution of many issues. While these improvements may not seem significant externally, they ultimately laid the groundwork for a stronger leap forward.

First Closed Beta (March 2023~) Conducted a closed beta for Zepeto creators. Zepeto uses Unity as a development studio for creators. Launched a landing page in January and granted access to users who left their emails on March 29. Although the number of people who actually used UModeler X was not as high as the number who applied, we were able to receive helpful feedback from real Zepeto creators, which greatly aided in improving UModeler X. Improved rigging and export features to accommodate various body types of Zepeto. Opened the Official UModeler X Manual Site, built using the Docusaurus solution. Second Closed Beta (July 2023~) Held an invitation event. Invitations could be received either from someone who was already invited or by applying directly on the website. In retrospect, it might have been better not to conduct this event as part of a viral marketing strategy. Began to inform existing UModeler users about UModeler X. We created a new UModeler X category in the UModeler Discord channel and simultaneously announced the news of UModeler X's second closed beta in communities where Unity developers are active. Released the first demo video. Released tutorial videos to help get started with UModeler X, serving as an excellent guide. Added an auto-rigging feature similar to the Mixamo concept. Setting guide points automatically generates a skeleton for human and quadruped meshes and assigns weights to vertices. Implemented AI texturing in collaboration with the game company nerdystar, working with Stable Diffusion + WebUI. This allows for direct projection of AI-generated images onto 3D models in the scene view, simplifying the cumbersome texture creation process. Open Beta (September 2023~) From this point on, anyone can use UModeler X simply by signing up. Released the second demo video. Launched UModeler X on the Unity Asset Store. Now anyone can download UModeler Hub from the Asset Store and use UModeler X. UModeler X with AI-Texturing Opened a course on Unity's Official Online Learning Site (learn.unity.com) for getting started with UModeler X. Getting Started with UModelerX - Unity Learn Created a demo video showcasing the advantages of using UModeler X with Synty Studios' assets in Unity, allowing for direct editing and animation.

Our goal with UModeler X is to upgrade the Unity editor, used by over 1.1 million people monthly, into an easier and more convenient tool for creating 3D content. If anyone using the Unity editor can fully unleash their imagination with UModeler X, the world will become more exciting and colorful. To achieve such a world, UModeler X will continue to develop and evolve without cease.

This year, we plan to implement the sketch-based smart modeling that made the original UModeler special, into UModeler X as well. Also, hotspot texturing and the Curve editor are expected to be integrated into UModeler X soon. Additionally, AI Texturing version 2.0 is waiting for you. We are preparing many more features, so you can look forward to them.

To install UModeler X, you first need to install the Hub from the Unity Asset Store. This Hub is responsible for the installation and updating of UModeler X and allows for the download of other necessary assets. After running the Hub, create an account and log in to install UModeler X.

If you have any improvements, questions, or issues you'd like to discuss while using UModeler X, try using the UModeler Discord server. You can receive direct feedback from developers or other UModeler X users there. You can also get the latest news about UModeler X on this server. Feel free to inquire through the UModeler Unity Forum or Email. UModeler Discord Server Unity UModeler Forum contact.support@umodeler.com
For the latest information, follow UModeler on Twitter, Facebook, and Instagram.

Hello, As we approach the end of July, we're here with a new blog post. Over the past month, there have been many updates not only in development but also in our business model. In this blog post, we will share these updates with you.
documents.s: UModeler X License Model, Technical Roadmap and Latest Updates

documents.t: Since last September, UModeler X has received various feedback from approximately 4,200 users during the beta testing phase, making it a more powerful and stable tool. Finally, the licensing model for UModeler X has been somewhat finalized. Even after the new licensing model is applied, the various modeling, rigging, painting, and AI texturing tools provided in the existing beta version will continue to be available for free with the Basic license. The Plus License includes all the features of the Basic license, along with the core features and major tools of UModeler, aiming to fully replace the original UModeler. Existing UModeler users will have the benefit of purchasing the Plus license at an upgrade price. This Plus license is scheduled to be released as an early bird version in September 2024, with the official version launching on the Unity Asset Store in November 2024. The Pro and Team licenses, which will be subscription-based, are set to be unveiled early next year. These licenses will not only include all the features of the Plus license but also provide the fastest access to the latest features of UModeler X. For more information on the UModeler X license, please refer to the FAQ page below. UModeler X License Model Go to

Along with the confirmation of the licensing model, the technical roadmap has also been somewhat defined. All upcoming license models will include the Texture Parameter Tool and Face Color Tool currently available in the Beta version. The Plus license will feature the core functions of the original UModeler, including Sketch-Based Modeling, Hotspot Texturing, Array Tool, Follow Tool, and more. The Pro and Team licenses will offer advanced features to enhance 3D content creation, such as AI Texturing 2.0, Curve Editor, and Pelt Unwrap. Additionally, new features will be continually added. The technical roadmap until the first quarter of 2025 is as follows. Please note that the following list of features may be subject to change depending on circumstances. Technical Roadmap (July 2024 - March 2025) July 2024 - Beta Version Texture Parameter Tool Face Color Tool September 2024 - Plus License Early Bird Version Array Tool (similar to Clone Tool in UModeler) Export Tool (supports .OBJ, .STL, .PLY) PushPull Tool Sketch-based Modeling November 2024 - Plus License Official Version Follow Tool Hotspot Texturing Multi-channel UV Editing And more February 2025 - Pro, Team Licenses AI Texturing 2.0 Curve Editor Pelt Unwrap Voxel Editor Plan Editor And more
We would like to share the major updates of UModeler X from the past month. From version 0.19.20 to 0.19.24, various features have been added to assist in level design.

Create As Static Object: This option allows UModelerX Objects to be created as Static by default. Static Option: This option sets the Static options for UModelerX Objects when the Create As Static Object option is enabled. Always Enable Grid Snap: This option allows the Grid Snapping feature to always be enabled when a UModelerX Object is selected. Create Under Root: This option allows UModelerX Objects to be created without a parent object.

Hello, UModeler X Users! In this June blog, we bring you various exciting news. From the completion of the Low Poly tutorial series and the release of the Zepeto item guidebook to the latest updates in UModeler X and the results of the game jam held with FIA, there's plenty to catch up on. Check out the latest developments and community activities with UModeler X!
documents.s: Low Poly Tutorials, Zepeto Guidebook, UModeler X Enhancements, and FIA Game Jam Results

documents.t: The Low Poly tutorial series for beginners is finally complete! With the newly added "Low Poly Isometric Room" tutorial, we now have a comprehensive learning course that covers everything from the basics of 3D modeling to practical projects for beginners. This tutorial series is designed to be easy to follow, even for beginners, and includes the following courses: Basic Tutorial: Modeling, Rigging, and Painting Modes Basic Tutorial: UV Editor Guide Low Poly Table and Chair Tutorial Guide Low Poly Tower Tutorial Guide Low Poly Building Tutorial Guide New! Low Poly Isometric Room Tutorial Final Tutorial: Synty Studio Assets and Mixamo Animation Integration Guide You can check out the tutorials in order from the page below. Basics Tutorial This tutorial is designed for beginners to give you an overview of the features and basic usage of UModeler X. Learn Each tutorial is structured in a step-by-step manner, allowing users to practice through real projects. The newly added "Low Poly Isometric Room" tutorial, in particular, provides detailed instructions on creating an isometric style room, helping you enhance your 3D modeling skills. All tutorial videos can be found on the UModeler X manual page. Each video is provided with friendly explanations, making it easy for beginners to understand and follow along. We hope this tutorial series will be greatly helpful in your 3D modeling journey with UModeler X, and we look forward to bringing you even better content and features in the future.
documents.s: Completion of the Low Poly Tutorial Series

documents.t: This tutorial is designed for beginners to give you an overview of the features and basic usage of UModeler X. Learn

We are excited to introduce the newly released Zepeto Item Creation Guidebook. This guidebook covers everything from the basics to advanced applications, enabling even those who are not familiar with Unity to create Zepeto items easily using UModeler X. This guidebook is extremely useful for beginners who are creating Zepeto items for the first time, as well as for intermediate and advanced users who want to create items more conveniently. The guidebook includes the following contents: Chapter 1 - Getting Started with UModeler X: Introduction to essential software and installation process. Chapter 2 - Exploring the UModeler X Interface: Navigating the interface and utilizing tools. Chapter 3 - Basic Modeling: Basic elements and functions of 3D modeling. Chapter 4 - Modeling Application: Applying modeling in actual projects. Chapter 5 - UV Mapping, Texturing, and Painting: Techniques for UV mapping and texturing. Chapter 6 - Rigging: Bringing models to life through rigging processes. Chapter 7.1 - Masking: Importance and effective creation and application of masks. Chapter 7.2 - Upload: How to upload completed items to Zepeto Studio. Zepeto Item Guidebook Go to The video below is the tutorial video for Chapter 4, one of the seven videos created for the Zepeto Item Creation Guidebook.
documents.s: Release of the Zepeto Item Guidebook

documents.t: Over the past month, UModeler X has had three updates: 0.19.17, 0.19.18, and 0.19.19. These updates bring various improvements that make your 3D modeling experience more convenient and efficient. Key updates include: Improved Vertex/Edge Picking: The mouse cursor now highlights and allows selection when it is near edges and vertices, making element editing much easier. Distance Property Addition: You can now input element distances numerically, enabling more precise work. Improved Bridge Tool: The Bridge tool has been enhanced to easily fill holes. Improved UModelerize: Addition of Hierarchically option. Changing the setting for Merge Vertices option to be adjustable in the Preference window. Shortcut Addition for Backface Select in Vertex/Edge/Face Tool: This allows for faster and more efficient work. For more details, please refer to the release notes. UModeler X Release Notes Go to We hope these updates will enhance your 3D modeling experience with UModeler X. We will continue to meet your expectations with ongoing improvements and updates.

The Future Inspire Jam #5, held this month, has concluded successfully. This game jam saw many creative game projects using UModeler X, drawing significant attention. Here are the winning entries and major news from the jam.

Hello, In this blog post, we'll share updates about the online manual, updates related to URP/HDRP for UModeler X, and news about our new tutorial videos.
documents.s: Online Manual Revamp, HDRP/URP Improvements, and New Tutorials

documents.t: Firstly, we integrated the Release Notes and FAQ page, which were on separate sites and somewhat inconvenient to access, into the online manual. At the same time, we separated some of the FAQ content dealing with error handling into a separate Trouble Shooting page to make it easier for users to address errors that occur during authentication and when using UModeler X. Release Note Check FAQ Check Trouble Shooting Check We also added a new The Use of UModeler X category to gather content on how to apply UModeler X. Currently, you can find videos on low-poly modeling, guides for collaboration with Synty Studio and Mixamo, and various videos on creating items for Zepeto in this category. We plan to continuously update this space with documents and videos on various UModeler X tips and techniques. Low Poly Guide Check Synty and Mixamo Collabo Check Zepeto Item Check As many of you know, not only the existing UModeler meshes but also general static meshes and skinned meshes can be converted into UModeler X meshes for direct editing in Unity. We have gathered guides related to this in the Getting Started > Mesh Data Conversion category to make them more accessible.

With the UModeler X 0.19.4 update, we have resolved most of the issues that arose with URP and HDRP. For example, the issue where hidden elements were selected when Camera Based Select was activated, and issues that occurred in modeling/rigging/painting modes when using tools with brushes, have been fixed.

We released a tutorial video on making low-poly buildings. A user's request recently made us realize that we had not created demos or videos related to low-poly due to focusing on showing that UModeler X is capable of high-poly modeling, rigging, and painting. Many indie game developers likely use UModeler X for creating low-poly meshes. So starting with this low-poly building tutorial video, we plan to create various low-poly tutorial videos. I will make time to create and showcase tutorials on mugs, chairs, towers, barrels, etc. If there's a tutorial you would like to see, please suggest it on our Discord server. These tutorials are also easy for me to make quickly using UModeler X, even though I come from a programmer background.

UModeler Inc. has obtained a patent in the United States for a "METHOD AND 3D MODELING ENGINE FOR MANAGING MODELING DATA DURING 3D MODELING". This technology covers an efficient method for creating and editing 3D data in a real-time graphics environment. Thanks to this, it has been possible to develop a high-performance 3D modeling solution in the Unity editor using the C# language.
documents.s: Obtaining a US Patent for 3D Modeling Technology

documents.t: We will be attending GDC 2024 in San Francisco from March 20th to 22nd. We're so excited about attending GDC after a long time. If anyone else is going, please contact me via email (contact.support@umodeler.com) or DM on Discord/Facebook. I'll share the news from GDC when we return.

That's all for this blog update. The various issues and feedback that you share via Discord and email play a significant role in making UModeler X more stable and useful. If you encounter any inconveniences while using UModeler X, please feel free to inform us through the UModeler Discord server or email. UModeler Discord Server Go Now We'll return with more new content in the next blog. See you then!
Hello UModeler X users! Today, we're excited to share some thrilling and valuable updates with you. In this blog post, we'll cover the latest news, updates, and our achievements with UModeler X.
documents.s: UModeler X Latest News - Game Jam, Updates, and Achievements

documents.t: First, let's talk about the UModeler X Game Jam. This game jam, hosted in collaboration with Future Inspire Academy (FIA), focuses on creating 3D games using Unity. FIA is a non-profit organization dedicated to providing game development education in a fun and flexible manner. They offer Unity challenges, game creation tasks, mentoring, and a gamified leaderboard to support developers worldwide. We sponsor this game jam. Participants will use UModeler X's rigging, painting, AI texturing, and modeling features to develop creative games. All participants must submit their projects on GitHub, with primary assets created using UModeler X. For detailed rules and participation, check the links below. UModeler X Game Jam Site FIA Discord Server

Over the past month we released six updates from version 0.19.11 to 0.19.16. Here are some of the key updates: Weight Mirror Tool Addition This tool allows you to easily copy the weight values of vertices from one side to the symmetric counterpart in symmetric objects, significantly improving efficiency. Standard Brush Tool Improvement You can now push in the opposite direction of the surface normal by holding the Ctrl key while brushing. Additionally, you can adjust the brush size by holding the Shift key and moving the mouse up and down. Auto Generate Mesh Collider Addition The Auto Generate Mesh Collider property has been added to the Preferences window and the Local Settings tool of UModeler X objects. This feature allows new objects to automatically reflect the mesh editing, enhancing level design convenience.

We're proud to announce that UModeler and UModeler X have been selected as valuable assets for VRChat content creation on the globally popular VR metaverse platform VRChat. Now, VRChat creators can use UModeler and UModeler X to craft even more impressive content. VRChat Picks in the Unity Asset Store

This game is now available on Steam, XBox and Nintendo Switch, and it has been well-received by gamers worldwide. This success story underscores the excellence of UModeler. Enjoy enhanced productivity with UModeler and UModeler X. XBox Steam Nintendo Switch These are the latest updates from UModeler X. We hope you continue to enjoy creating with UModeler X. Stay tuned for more updates and exciting news!

documents.t: UModeler participated as a sponsor at Unite 2024 (September 18-20, 2023), drawing significant attention from developers worldwide. Notably, we received exceptional interest not only from game developers but also from university educators and students, highlighting how in-Unity 3D modeling capabilities can significantly lower the barriers to education and learning.

A remarkable achievement was the 'UModeler X Plus Early Bird' version reaching #1 in overall popularity on the Unity Asset Store just two days after its release on September 14th. This incredible success demonstrates developers' high expectations and trust in UModeler X Plus.

documents.t: UModeler X Plus Early Bird has undergone remarkable development through seven updates, from 0.91.1 to 0.92.0. Let's look at the key updates.
Align Tool: Precisely align model vertices according to various criteria Normal Painting Tool: Advanced functionality for converting height maps to normal maps

Enhanced Tablet Support: Automatic brush opacity and size adjustment based on pressure sensitivity Clear Unused Assets: Efficient scene data cleanup Primitive Shapes: Automatic object naming functionality Vertex Position Editor: Precise position editing in local/world coordinate systems

Improved compatibility with Unity 6.0+ Multi-material handling optimization Enhanced UV and normal calculation accuracy Various bug fixes and performance improvements For more detailed information, please check the UModeler X Plus Release Notes.
UModeler X Plus 1.0's official release is scheduled for Wednesday, November 20th. As previewed in September, it will feature significantly upgraded capabilities.

Upgraded SketchUp Style Modeling: Continuous improvements for intuitive modeling workflow Follow Tool: Enhanced power with progressive generation capabilities added to the existing robust Follow tool Hotspot Texturing: Improved UI/UX and trim sheet support for enhanced texturing experience

Enhanced Save System: Simultaneous .asset and .unity scene file saving for lighter project management Humanoid Avatar Support: Complete Humanoid Avatar support in rigging mode for streamlined animation application
After careful consideration of user feedback, UModeler has enhanced its licensing policy:
Free for both commercial and non-commercial use Updates focused on major bug fixes Internet connection required User data collection for service improvement Current feature set maintained

Premium license supporting both commercial and non-commercial use Rapid updates and priority feedback implementation Offline usage available Optional user data collection Advanced features including SketchUp-style modeling, Hotspot texturing, Array tool/modifier, Follow tool, Align tool, and Normal painting

Hello everyone! Welcome to 2025! Today, we're excited to share the latest updates to UModeler X.

This update introduces several new features designed to boost your productivity. Notable additions to the Unity toolbar include two new popup windows: UMX Display Settings and UMX Snap Settings. These windows eliminate the need to navigate through Preferences' options to adjust display and snap settings during your workflow! For those who love symmetrical modeling, we've enhanced the Mirror Object tool with a preview feature that shows the mirrored parts before creation, making symmetrical modeling more intuitive and efficient. Character artists will appreciate our new Create Root Bone Structure feature, which automatically generates animation root bones and geometry object hierarchies for rigging. Say goodbye to complex manual setup before rigging! We're also introducing the Element ID Selector, a powerful troubleshooting tool that visually displays IDs for vertices, edges, and faces, helping you quickly identify and resolve modeling issues. Element ID Selector Go to Documentation Repeat Function Go to Documentation Additionally, we've renamed the Line tool to Knife tool and moved it to the Add group. The Drawing mode now features a new Polyline tool, which is continuously being improved!

UModeler X Plus introduces over 20 new features compared to the Basic version. Moving forward, Plus will focus on stability improvements and performance optimization rather than new feature additions. The upcoming Pro license will include all Plus features while continuously adding new functionality. Pro will be offered as a subscription model to ensure sustainable company operations and stable development of UModeler X. This model will enable us to provide regular updates, new feature development, and enhanced technical support.

documents.t: We acknowledge recent feedback regarding stability issues with UModeler X Plus, particularly with the Polyline and PushPull tools for SketchUp-style modeling. We've also noted concerns about errors when switching between game and edit modes with Domain Reloading disabled. We sincerely apologize for not meeting your expectations regarding stability. Our development team is working diligently to address these issues, and we're committed to improving stability throughout January to ensure a smooth experience for all users. We deeply appreciate your feedback and patience as we work to make UModeler X more reliable and stable.

documents.t: Hello UModeler X Plus users, We are excited to announce that UModeler X Plus 1.0 official version will be released on November 20th. Since the Early Bird version release in September, our team has been working diligently to prepare for the official version. However, we need to share one piece of news that might disappoint you. The SketchUp-style modeling features we promised in September won't be fully implemented by the 20th. Implementing these features perfectly in the new UModeler X architecture has presented more technical challenges than anticipated. We plan to enhance this functionality through continuous updates after the 1.0 release. Specifically, the Line tool will be moved to the Add group and renamed to Knife tool to better reflect its polygon-cutting functionality. Additionally, a new Poly Line tool will be added to the Drawing group to support SketchUp-style modeling. As for Hotspot texturing, we will first provide it at the existing UModeler level and implement additional features gradually after the release. To compensate for these adjustments, we have prepared several new features: Normal Painting (released in October) Humanoid Avatar support Enhanced Display/Debug/Snap Settings UI Separate Parts Tool Offline use available We are confident these new features will significantly improve your 3D content creation workflow. We are prioritizing the development of SketchUp-style modeling and Hotspot texturing, aiming to complete them within this year. We will regularly share development progress updates with you. Here are the key features included in UModeler X Plus 1.0: SketchUp Style Modeling (including PushPull tool) ver 0.7 Hotspot Texturing Tool Follow Tool Array Modifier and Tools Normal Painting .OBJ, .STL, .PLY Exporter Humanoid Avatar support Multi UV support Scene saving support for UModeler X 3D model data Enhanced Debug, Display Settings UI World and Increment options added to Snap Panel window Separate Parts Tool Side Stair Tool Enhanced Edge Eraser Tool Offline use available Post-1.0 UModeler X Plus Roadmap in 2024 SketchUp Style Modeling ver 1.0 Supports for connecting outer polygons with inner holes. Enhance the stability. and more. Additional Hotspot Texturing features Trim sheet Group-based hotspots Improved Pivot Gizmo system One more thing—the Plus version will not participate in the Black Friday sale, and the early bird pricing will end then. We look forward to bringing you the official release news on November 20th. Thank you for your continued support.
documents.s: UModeler X Plus 1.0 Release Date Announcement

documents.t: made with UModeler X by nerdystar The AI texturing feature of UModeler X is integrated with the Stable Diffusion web UI, allowing you to easily apply images to models. By utilizing this feature, you can complete complex and time-consuming texture work quickly and easily. The guide documents explain the overall process for using AI texturing, from installation to usage methods and recommended settings. Detailed guidance is provided, along with step-by-step instructional videos.
You can learn how to model simple 3d low poly models here Learn

Edges are the lines that make up a mesh, and moving or editing an edge affects the elements associated with it. You can view properties related to Edges by pressing the keyboard shortcut Shift+2, or by using the scene top buttons. note Shortcut Shift+Click Drag​ When you select an edge and perform a Shift held down with click drag, the selected edge moves while simultaneously creating a new face in the direction of the movement.
When you select an edge and perform a Shift held down with click drag, the selected edge moves while simultaneously creating a new face in the direction of the movement.
These are the properties that are displayed for the Element group when an edge is selected.
Properties that allow you to choose how the mesh is displayed.
Allows edges to be visible or hidden.

Shows or hides the edge set by the Mark Seam tool. note The Mark Seam tool is a tool for UV editing, and you can use the Mark Seam tool in the Surface group to select edges to utilize in the UV Editor tool.
Property that allows you to set how the edge is selected.

Allows you to set whether opposite facing edges are selected. When the Backface Select property is off, opposite facing edges are not selected. When the Backface Select property is on, opposite edges are selected as well.

This property selects only the currently visible edges based on the camera. When the Camera Based Select property is off, edges that are hidden by the camera are also selected. When the Camera Based Select property is on, edges that are hidden by the camera are not selected.

This property selects only face edge edges. When the Border Rect Select property is off, all edges are selected. When the Border Rect Select property is on, only the edges of the face and any openings are selected. tip This is a great way to find punctures, or to find less connected vertices.

This property will select based on weight edges that are adjacent to the selected edge in the Scene. The selected edges and the range you set based on the weight are displayed in color, usually as a soft circle.

A graph-like property that determines the shape of the Soft Selection. Tap the graph next to the Soft Selection Curve property to edit it. Example of Curve shape Examples of selection shape changes by Curve shape. Example 1 Example 2
A property that sets the range over which soft selection is applied from the selected edge. In Unity, 1m = 1.0, so for 0.5, it will select up to 50cm from the selected edge.
A Property that is displayed when an element is moved indicates the distance traveled.

Editable Mesh is the main 3D model editing feature of UModelerX. When you create a UModelerX object, it is added as a component to the object, and you can check it in the Inspector tab. Editable Mesh allows you to create and edit a mesh that can be directly edited. It has three modes, and additionally, it provides two editors that can be used by opening a window named 'Editor'.

Modeling Mode is the foundational mode of Editable Mesh, with the primary function being mesh editing. Modeling Mode is categorized into tools with various functions, properties that represent the detailed settings of the tools, and groups that bundle the tools together.
Rigging Mode is for animating 3D models. Rigging Mode includes tools that allow for skinning, which connects the mesh and bones during the rigging process.
The Painting mode is a mode where you can add or edit textures and colors on a mesh through various painting-related tools, layers, and brushes.

AI Texturing in UModeler X is a feature that works in conjunction with the Stable Diffusion web UI to allow you to easily image your models. Watch the step-by-step video below to get up to speed quickly.
Exports the current UModeler X mesh to a file in a specified format. note This feature is exclusive to UModeler X Plus

Create Folder: A folder will be created, and .OBJ, .STL, and .MTL files will be exported within it. Export Material: A material file (.MTL) will be created. Export Vertex Colors: Adds RGB channels to each vertex. This format may not be compatible with all programs that load .obj files. Export Unit: Supports Meter, CentiMeter, and MilliMeter units. Export Face Type: Supports Triangles, Quads, and Polygons face types. Optimize: Supported only when Export Face Type is set to Triangles. Minimizes redundant information during export.
Create Folder: A folder will be created, and .OBJ, .STL, and .MTL files will be exported within it. stl Format: Supports Binary and Ascii formats.

Create Folder: A folder will be created, and .OBJ, .STL, and .MTL files will be exported within it. Export Face Type: Supports Triangles, Quads and Polygons face types. Optimize: Supported only when Export Face Type is set to Triangles. Minimizes redundant information during export.

The Stable Diffusion web UI allows you to install several add-ons called Extensions. To use UModeler X's AI texturing features, you need to install an extension of the Stable Diffusion web UI called ControlNet.

Open the Extensions tab Open the Extensions tab in the web UI. Install by URL Within the Extensions tab, open the Install from URL tab. Enter your ControlNet repository URL. Enter https://github.com/Mikubill/sd-webui-controlnet.git in the field next to URL for extension's git repository. Click the Install button Click the Install button and wait a few seconds. When you see the message Installed into stable-diffusion-webui\extensions\sd-webui-controlnet. Use Installed tab to restart, the installation is complete. Update and restart. Go to the Installed tab. Click Check for updates, then Click Apply and restart UI.
ControlNet has several models available. ControlNet 1.1 includes 14 models that are currently in beta testing.

Access the model download link Access the ControlNet 1.1 model download page. Download the .pth file From the page, download the model files with the file extension ending in .pth. The total capacity of the 14 models is approximately 18.8 GB, and you can download them selectively if you don't need to download all of them. If the size is a concern, we recommend downloading only control_v11f1p_sd15_depth.pth. Move the downloaded model files. Place the downloaded model files into the path stable-diffusion-webui/extensions/sd-webui-controlnet/models in the folder where the Stable Diffusion web UI is installed, and the models will be applied.

Here is an alternative way to install ControlNet. This method allows you to view a list of the different extensions available in the Stable Diffusion web UI and easily install them. Open the Extensions tab Open the Extensions tab and Click Available. Check the Load from button Verify that the address shown next to Load from: is https://raw.githubusercontent.com/AUTOMATIC1111/stable-diffusion-webui-extensions/master/index.json. It is set to the above address by default if you haven't modified it. Click the Load from: button. You will see several extensions available for installation. Search ControlNet. Enter sd-webui-controlnet in the Search input part. Install ControlNet Find sd-webui-controlnet manipulations in the list and Click the Install button to the right of the description. The image below is marked Installed because it was already installed above. Confirm installation Once the installation is complete, return to the Installed tab to see the installed extensions. Apply and restart Pressing the Apply and restart UI button will actually apply the installed extensions. With this method, you can easily add not only the ControlNet extension, but many other extensions as well.
documents.s: An alternative way to install ControlNet and its extensions.

documents.t: Faces are the faces that make up the mesh, and moving or editing a face affects the elements associated with it. You can view the properties of a Face by pressing the keyboard shortcut Shift+3, or by using the buttons at the top of the scene.
These are the properties that are displayed for the Element group when a Face is selected.
Properties that allow you to choose how the face is extruded when using the Extrude Tool. The Extrude Tool can be used to extrude or extrude faces using the keyboard shortcut Shift+Click Drag.
This is the default property for the Extrude Tool, which causes the Extrude Tool to run based on the gizmo.

The Extrude Tool will run on an individual face-by-face basis, aligned with the face's normal direction. note The difference with the Vertex Normal property is that for Individual Normal, the Extrude tool is run for each face, so the selected faces are all extruded or pushed apart.
The Extrude tool is run in the normal direction of the faces.
Runs the Extrude tool in the average normal direction of the selected faces.
This property allows you to choose how the mesh is displayed.
Allows you to show or hide edges.
Property that allows you to set how the face is selected.

Allows you to set whether opposite faces are selected. When the Backface Select property is off, opposite faces are not selected. When the Backface Select property is on, opposite faces will be selected as well.

This property selects only the currently visible face based on the camera. When the Camera Based Select property is off, faces hidden by the camera are also selected. When the Camera Based Select property is on, faces that are hidden by the camera are not selected.
This property selects faces in the Scene that are adjacent to the selected face based on their weight. The selected faces and the range you set based on the weight are colored, usually a soft circle.

This is a property that allows you to manage faces as a group, making them appear to be connected or disconnected from each other. A group of selected faces will smoothly connect surfaces, while other groups will appear disconnected. tip Proper use of the Smoothing Group property can help you achieve smooth surfaces with a small number of faces, and can help with optimization.
This property automatically sets a smoothing group between selected faces.
This property resets all currently set smoothing groups.

This property selects the face set to the group when the button corresponding to the group is pressed. tip In addition to smoothing, the Selected Smoothing Group property can also be used to manage complex models in groups, as it makes it easy to select faces. UModeler X is an all-in-one 3D asset creation solution offered as a Unity plugin. With UModeler X, you can create and edit high-quality 3D models directly in the Unity Editor using its advanced modeling, UV editing, rigging, painting tools, and AI texturing capabilities. You can find more information about UModeler X on the website below. UModeler X Introduction Page UModeler X Manual Site Unity Asset Store

Using UModeler X allows for direct editing of 3D models in the Unity game engine, offering higher productivity compared to relying solely on external tools like Blender, Max, or Maya. Additionally, UModeler X enables you to modify 3D data created in these external tools right within Unity. Without UModeler X, you would have to undergo the cumbersome process of editing in an external tool and then re-importing into Unity. However, UModeler X eliminates this hassle. Beyond just modifying 3D data, UModeler X allows you to create high-quality 3D models from scratch within Unity, enabling you to see them immediately in the final scene. This saves a significant amount of effort and time.
documents.s: What are the advantages of using UModeler X compared to Blender, Maya, 3ds Max, Photoshop and Substance Painter etc?

documents.t: UModeler X offers a variety of key features for free, accessible to everyone. This policy will continue, and additional features will be offered as paid options in the future. The current pricing model under consideration is as follows. Please note that it is subject to change. Basic Plus Pro Free (Asset Store) $199 (Asset Store) Subscription Basic 3D Editor Package + Essential 3D Editor Package + Advanced 3D Editor Package + 3D Asset Package + Advanced 3D Asset Package + Unlimited Expansion Pack Update Technical Support Technical Support Top-priority Technical Support Team Member Management Personal Personal Professional and Enterprise 2024 UModeler X Plus's Discount Events For exact discount periods and information, please refer to the announcements on UModeler's official channels: Discord, Twitter(X), or Facebook. Period Plus Upgrade Fee (UModeler → UModeler X Plus) September 2024 $49 (UNITE Special, 75% off) $40 October 2024 $99 (Early Bird, 50% off) $70 From November 2024 $199 (Official Release) $99 The upgrade fee will be automatically applied in the Unity Asset Store if you purchased UModeler there. The upgrade fee may change based on circumstances. The Basic version is provided for free with basic features, while the Plus version includes additional essential features, and the Pro version offers an advanced 3D editor package along with member management functionality. UModeler X Basic: To allow users to experience basic features and perform various modeling tasks, the Basic 3D Editor Package is provided for free. This package includes features such as modeling, rigging, painting, and AI texturing available during the open beta period (September 2023~). The stabilized version of UModeler X Basic can be downloaded for free from the Unity Asset Store based on feedback from the beta version. UModeler X Plus: To enable more precise and faster work, UModeler X Basic has been enhanced with essential features from the original UModeler, including sketch-based modeling, hotspot texturing, the Follow tool, and the Array tool. And Additional tools, such as the Export tool and Normal Painting feature, will be included in the Plus version as well. This more comprehensive tool, UModeler X Plus, is scheduled to be released on the Unity Asset Store around November 2024 and we're planning to upgrade the Plus pack annually with new expansion pack features. UModeler X Pro: To fully realize your imagination, this version includes the Advanced 3D Editor Package. This package is set to include features such as AI Texturing 2.0, Curve Editor, Smart UV Unwrap, Text to 3D, CSG Modeling, Parametric Primitive Editor, SDF Editor, Blend Shape Tool, and Retopology Editor etc. The Unlimited Expansion Pack Updates will provide access to all future UModeler X expansion packs as soon as they are developed. This version is available through a subscription model to ensure the fastest updates.

documents.t: One of the main reasons for developing UModeler X, despite the existing UModeler being already released, was the limitation of the original UModeler in editing high-polygon models. Additionally, since the original UModeler was designed with a focus on 3D modeling, it faced challenges in implementing rigging and painting features. For these reasons, UModeler X was developed to offer higher performance and scalability, and we successfully launched its open beta in September 2023. Based on feedback from the beta version, we launched the paid version of UModeler X Plus as an Early Bird release on the Asset Store in September 2024, with the official version finally released on November 20, 2024. You can see a rough comparison of the current open beta version of UModeler X, the original UModeler, and the highly advanced UModeler X Plus, which combines the features of both, in the table below. Category Function UModeler UModeler X Basic UModeler X Plus Modeling Polygon Editing ✔️ ✔️ ✔️ └ Array(Clone) Tool ✔️ ❌ ✔️ └ Follow Tool ✔️ ❌ ✔️ SketchUp Style Modeling ✔️ ❌ ✔️ Push Pull ✔️ ❌ ✔️ Modifiers ❌ ✔️ ✔️ └ Array Modifier ❌ ❌ ✔️ .OBJ Exporter ✔️ ❌ ✔️ .PLY, .STL Exporter ❌ ❌ ✔️ Separate Parts Tool ❌ ❌ ✔️ Processable Face Count Low-poly High-poly Low/High-poly UV Editing UV Unwrap ✔️ ✔️ ✔️ └ LSCM Algorithm UV Unwrap ❌ ✔️ ✔️ Multi UV Channel Editing ❌ ❌ ✔️ Hotspot Texturing ✔️ ❌ ✔️ Rigging Bone Editing ❌ ✔️ ✔️ Weight Editing ❌ ✔️ ✔️ Auto Rigging ❌ ✔️ ✔️ └ Auto Weight ❌ ✔️ ✔️ └ Build Bone ❌ ✔️ ✔️ Humanoid Support ❌ ❌ ✔️ Painting 3D Painting ❌ ✔️ ✔️ Layer-based Texturing ❌ ✔️ ✔️ Brush Editing ❌ ✔️ ✔️ Normal Painting ❌ ❌ ✔️ AI Texturing 1.0 ❌ ✔️ ✔️ System Offline Support ✔️ ❌ ✔️ We have also prepared a UModeler X usage guide for existing UModeler users. We hope this document clearly explains which solution you should use, UModeler X or the existing UModeler

documents.t: Sketch-based modeling is currently seeing many reported improvements. These improvements are scheduled to be intensively implemented in December. Gizmo will support a wider range of coordinate axes. Currently, it only supports Unity's Local and Global, but this will be expanded to include Normal, Screen, and Custom support. A feature supporting Sharp edges will be added to Smoothing Groups. A Face group feature will be added that allows faces to be grouped and managed together. Group functionality and trim sheet capabilities will be added to hotspot texturing. Multi-objects Mirror tool will be newly added.

documents.t: The open beta for UModeler X began on September 1, 2023, showcasing key features such as modeling, rigging, painting, and AI texturing. The goal of this open beta was to incorporate as much user feedback as possible to create a more stable version of UModeler X. The open beta concluded on September 17, 2024, with the release of the paid model, UModeler X Plus. After the beta ended, the UModeler X Beta version transitioned to the Basic version, which remains available for use. The Basic version is offered for free and will primarily receive updates related to stability.

documents.t: By turning on the LightMap Static property in the Local Settings Tool under the Misc group, you can easily enable the light-related static options for GameObjects. documents.t: Prefab Assets contain both UModelerX editable data and renderable mesh data for convenience in file management. However, there are times when the UModelerX editable data becomes unnecessary, such as after editing is complete or when UModelerX is deleted from the prefab. In these instances, you can delete the data using the following method Select the Asset or Assets you wish to delete. Right-click and select 'Clean Unused UModelerX Data' and 'Clean Unused UModelerX Mesh', which can be found under Assets/UModeler X. Clean Unused UModelerX Data removes the UModelerX Data that is not being used. Clean Unused UModelerX Data and Mesh removes both the unused UModelerX Data and Unity Mesh Data. For Mesh Data, this operation deletes unused Mesh Data in MeshFilter, SkinnedMeshRenderer, and MeshCollider. We plan to support automatic removal in the future
documents.s: How to Remove UModelerX Data from Prefab Assets

documents.t: Using prefabs that include UModeler X prefabs can affect overall performance. This is mainly due to the Mesh.isReadable setting. When this setting is enabled, mesh data exists in both CPU and GPU accessible memory, impacting actual runtime memory usage. If the prefab size increases, the amount of data increases, which can affect loading times. Additionally, increased size can reduce cache hit rates, leading to performance degradation. Therefore, if you need to use a large number of prefab meshes, it might be more efficient to extract only the Unity meshes from the UModeler X prefabs. However, if the number of prefabs in the scene is not large or if they are low-poly meshes, using prefabs with UModeler X data should not significantly impact performance. Using prefabs with UModeler X allows for convenient editing directly with UModeler X without needing a separate export process. UModeler X related code is designed not to run at runtime, so it does not directly use CPU resources during runtime. Decisions on the extent of using UModeler X prefabs should be made after testing, considering the target hardware, types and amounts of meshes used, and their sizes.
documents.s: What impact does using prefabs with UModeler X data have on post-build performance?

documents.t: Create a Mesh with UModeler X: For this example, an alien mesh is created using the Iconsphere basic shape. Save Your Scene: After saving, the data for the objects created with UModeler X will be located in Scenes/[YourSceneName_UModeler]. Each object's data is named after the object itself. In this case, as the folder name is SampleScene, you can see the created objects in the project window as shown. Turn the Created Object into a Prefab: In the Hierarchy window, convert the iconsphere-alien object you created into a prefab as demonstrated in the provided GIF. Exporting for Use in Other Projects or Sharing: You can now export this prefab file along with the files in the SampleScene folder as a .unitypackage. This makes it possible to import and use it in other projects, or easily share it with friends. Before importing it into another project, ensure that UModeler X is installed in that project.
documents.s: How to Use a Specific Object Created with UModeler X in Another Project or Share It with Others

documents.t: note A pivot is a reference point for adjusting the position, rotation, scale, etc. of an object. Pivots are primarily used as the origin position of an object and are the reference points that define the position of a gizmo and the position of each element in object space. At the top of the Unity Editor, you will find a button that allows you to choose whether you want the Gizmo base to be a Pivot or the Center of the selected element. You can use these buttons to change the Gizmo's base point, and the position of the Gizmo will update based on the base point.
documents.s: How can I change the pivot of the selected elements?

documents.t: Yes, of course. You can edit externally created FBX files in Unity using UModeler X. Drag and drop the FBX file into your current Unity project to import it. Simply placing the mesh of the file in the scene does not allow you to edit it directly with UModeler X, even if it is installed. To edit the file, go to the upper right menu: Game Object > UModeler X. At this point, there are two options: UModelerize Merge Vertices: If there are multiple vertices in the same position, merge them all. UModelerize: UModelerize the original data without any changes. Choose one of the two options above to convert the imported data into a UModeler X mesh. This process is called UModelerizing. Once UModelerized, the UModeler X UI will appear in the Inspector window, and you can edit the mesh. If the mesh has rigging data, you can move to the Rigging tab to perform rigging-related editing tasks.
documents.s: Can I edit meshes in .FBX format created with external tools using UModeler X?

documents.t: Save the Scene of the project you are currently working on with UModeler X. When saving the Scene, UModeler X's configuration files are saved by creating a folder in the current Scene path with the format "SceneName_UModeler.” Copy the Scene file and the folder created above (in the format "SceneName_UModeler") along with its internal files. Create a new project. (Make sure to install UModeler X in the new project.) For the new project, paste the Scene and copied folders with the same structure as the original. When you open the copied Scene in the new project, you can use UModeler X as you were originally working with it.
documents.s: Can I import UModeler X model data that was created in a different project?

documents.t: The wireframe of the mesh is typically displayed in edit mode and is automatically deactivated in object mode. If you want to make it invisible even in edit mode, you can deactivate the [Debug/Display Wireframe] attribute in the Preferences menu, which appears when you click on the gear icon in the toolbar. Alternatively, in the Edge or Face tool, you can achieve the same effect by activating the Hide Edge Overlay as shown below.

By setting one of these materials as the default material for UModeler X in the Preferences window as shown below, it can be used as the default material for newly created UModeler X objects.

documents.t: You can resolve this by using the model's texture as a layer if there is a texture on the existing model. The method is as follows: Convert the model with a texture to a UModeler X model using UModelerize. Switch to the painting mode of UModeler X. After setting the resolution, properties, and background color, start painting by pressing the start painting button. Create a new Fill layer. Put the existing texture into the albedo slot of the Fill layer. You can see the existing texture applied. Painting is affected by the layer order, so move the layer you set up to the very bottom and create a Paint layer above it for painting. Paint using the desired brush and tools.
documents.s: How do I paint on an existing model with textures without it erasing all the textures?

documents.t: There are two methods to save a texture. The first method involves using the 'Output' found in 'Map Source'. This tool allows you to export your current painting data in its entirety, or by channel or layer, in PNG format. The second method is to use the 'Auto Save Textures' option located in 'Preferences'. When you exit the editor or painting mode, the texture is automatically saved. This property has been added since UModeler X version 0.13.2. In this case, the texture will be automatically overwritten and saved under the following conditions. Original material must have a texture. This texture must have the Read/Write option enabled. Supported texture extensions are .png, .jpg, .jpeg, .tga, .tpic, and .exr. Not available for Default UModeler materials.
documents.s: How do I save a painting texture?

documents.t: To apply a texture to a specific layer in Painting mode, you can use the 'Import Layer Image' function. This allows you to import an image directly onto the selected layer as illustrated below.
documents.s: How can I apply a texture to a specific layer in Painting mode?

documents.t: The installment-based version requires a PC with WebUI and Stable Diffusion installed. The AI Texturing feature in UModeler X, in conjunction with the Stable Diffusion web UI, simplifies the process of texturing your models with images. This feature makes complex and time-consuming texturing tasks quick and easy. UModeler X offers convenient methods for creating 2D images with AI and seamlessly projecting them onto 3D models. Since UModeler X connects to the WebUI and Stable Diffusion installed on your computer, there are no additional costs incurred. Therefore, you can freely utilize AI power to create 3D content without worrying about extra expenses.
documents.s: What is the installment-based version of the AI-Texture service?

documents.t: You can try AI Texturing starting from September 2023 using UModeler X ver 0.11.0 or later verions. For more detailed information about AI Texturing, please refer here.
documents.s: When can I try the AI texturing of UModeler X?

documents.t: Stable Diffusion works well with UModeler X if you are using version 1.5 series. We cannot guarantee 100% compatibility with other versions as we have not tested them. As for WebUI, if you have downloaded a version from AUTOMATIC1111, you should be able to use it without any issues. For more details, please refer to the WebUI Installation Guide.
documents.s: What are the recommended versions of Stable Diffusion and WebUI?

documents.t: Masking is a process that indicates whether the inner body mesh is hidden by clothing, preventing defects where the inner polygons stick out during animation. However, if the masking is not carefully done for the parts in contact with the clothing boundary, issues such as gaps on the skin may occur. I'll share some tips for doing boundary masking well. Improper masking technique The black masking goes beyond the T-shirt's boundaries, sticking out. When you export it and preview it in the playground level, the black-painted areas become transparent, creating the illusion that there's no skin underneath. Proper masking technique We'll attempt to correct the data and make it accurate. By modifying the sections that go past the T-shirt's boundaries to white, and precisely painting only the areas inside the T-shirt that should be concealed in black, the skin will appear as intended.
documents.s: T-shirt boundary masking work tip using UModeler X

documents.t: This is a solution to the issue of mesh distortion around the ankle area when creating long pants, as seen in the examples above. Cause The problem occurs when there are no weight values around the ankle, but the weight transfer tool in rigging mode mistakenly obtains weight information from other parts or picks up small, incorrect values. Solution To resolve this issue, manually select the vertices at the very end of the ankle area, where weights should not be taken, and use the weight tool to set their weight values to 0. You will need to adjust the weights for the Foot, Heel, and Toes bones, making a total of 6 bones (one pair for each side) with weight values set to 0.
documents.s: Solution for mesh distortion in Zepeto long pants items caused by incorrect weight application at ankles

documents.t: Git is an essential distributed version control system for software development. As part of the installation process for the Stable Diffusion web UI, it is necessary to use Git Clone, which requires the installation of Git. The git clone command is used to copy project repository files from the web to your computer. This document describes the process of installing Git based on Windows.

go to the Git official download page. https://git-scm.com/downloads select the desired operating system. Here we will select Windows. Click on the Click here to download' part to download the Git installation file. If you want to install a specific version of Git, or choose a version that matches your computer's architecture (32-bit or 64-bit), scroll down on the webpage and click on the desired option: '32-bit Git for Windows Setup' or '64-bit Git for Windows Setup'. Typically, since most computers currently support 64-bit, you should select '64-bit Git for Windows Setup'. Now, you can install Git by running the downloaded installation file.

When installing Git on Windows, you can proceed with the default installation settings, but some options require manual selection. Please check the installation options below as you proceed with the installation. For other screens, you can simply continue by clicking 'Next' without making any special changes.

Select Components Windows Explorer integration: Right-click in Explorer to display a shortcut menu for Git commands. Git Bash Here: Make sure this is checked. This option will enable the 'Git Bash Here' command on right-click in Explorer. Adjusting your PATH environment. Git from the command line and also from 3rd-party software: This option adds Git to the PATH environment variable, allowing Git commands to be used in the command prompt or other 3rd-party software.
To verify that Git has been installed correctly, you should follow the steps below. You can check using either of the two methods provided below, depending on your preference.

Right-click on your desktop or file explorer at a location of your choice. select 'Open git bash here' from the dropdown menu that appears. In the newly opened Git Bash window, enter the command below. git --version Press Enter and if the screen displays the correct version information: 'git version x.x.x', the installation of Git has been successfully completed.

Shift+Right-click on the desktop or in a file explorer of your choice. select 'Open PowerShell window here' from the drop-down menu. In the newly opened PowerShell window, type git --version and press Enter. If the screen displays the version information 'git version x.x.x', the Git installation completed successfully. If no Git-related information appears at all, there may have been an issue during the installation process. In this case, you should review the installation steps or consider reinstalling Git from the beginning.

documents.t: UModeler X is a powerful 3D content creation solution available for use in the Unity editor. It is designed with an easy-to-understand interface that allows everyone from beginners to experts to easily use functions such as modeling, UV unwrapping, rigging, painting and AI texturing within the Unity editor. UModeler X provides a complete 3D content creation pipeline within the Unity environment, allowing users to perform all 3D content creation tasks within Unity without the need for separate external 3D programs. Below are the main categories of this manual and a brief description of each category.

This is a guide for first-time users of UModeler X. You can check step by step, from how to install it to basic usage methods.
