Explore the various menus in UModeler X to access a wide range of features. Each menu provides the tools and options necessary for specific tasks.
Use Element ID Selector to check the ID of the selected element, navigate to the previous or next element, or input an ID to select a desired element. For more details, see Element ID Selector.

Using the Element ID Selector, check the ID of the selected element, navigate to the previous or next element, and input an ID to select a desired element. Select "Tools > UModeler X > Element ID Selector" from the top menu.

Selected Object Displays the Name of the currently selected object. If nothing is selected "None" is displayed. Selected Type Displays the Type of selected Element. If nothing is selected "None" is displayed. Element ID Displays the selected Element's ID. If nothing is selected or multiple elements is selected, "-1" is displayed.

The Add group is a collection of tools that, when executed, will add each element (Vertex, Edge, Face). It usually contains tools that either add selected elements or add elements defined in the tool.
The Deform group is a collection of brush-like tools that deform surfaces.
The Drawing group is a collection of tools for creating planar shapes.
The Element group is located at the very top of the modeling mode and is a collection of properties related to each element (Vertex, Edge, Face, and Object).

In Modeling mode, the original mesh, Source Mesh, can be edited after selecting elements. There are three editable elements (Vertex, Edge, Face) and an Object to exit the editing state. You can choose which element to edit through the icons at the top of the scene. Depending on the selection of elements, there are properties within the Element group that are commonly applied to all, as well as properties that vary according to each specific element. Through the pages dedicated to each element below, you can easily find descriptions of each element and the properties that vary depending on the element selected. 📄️ Vertex 📄️ Edge 📄️ Face 📄️ Object

After selecting each element (vertex, edge, face), you can create new elements in a protruding or pushing manner in the direction of movement by moving the selected elements using Shift+click-drag. note For face elements, you can choose how the faces protrude using the Extrude Option property within the Face Element group properties.
These are the properties that are commonly applied to each element within the Element group.
This is a property that allows you to choose the display mode of the mesh.
Displays faces as translucent. tip Using the XRay Mode property, you can easily view elements located on the backside of complex models.
This is a property that allows you to set the selection mode for elements.

You can set whether to select elements that are facing the opposite side. When the Backface Select property is turned off, elements facing the opposite side are not selected. When the Backface Select property is turned on, elements facing the opposite side are also selected.

This is a property that allows for the selection of only the elements currently visible from the camera's perspective. When the Camera Based Select property is turned off, elements obscured by the camera are also selected. When the Camera Based Select property is turned on, elements obscured by the camera are not selected.

This property allows for the selection of elements adjacent to the selected elements in the scene (Scene), based on a weighting system. Based on the set weight, the selected elements and the specified range are displayed in color, generally indicated by a smooth circular shape.
This is a property that activates Soft Selection.

This property, in the form of a graph, determines the shape of the weight curve for Soft Selection. You can edit it by clicking on the graph next to the Soft Selection Curve property. Example of Curve shape This is an example of how the selection shape changes depending on the Curve type.

This property sets the range over which soft selection is applied, starting from the selected elements. Since in Unity 1 meter equals 1.0, a value of 0.5 would mean that elements up to 50cm from the selected element are selected.
When you press the V key and move the gizmo (handle), you can move the selected element to the position of the vertex pointed by the mouse, or align the position of the element to that location.

Select a Vertex by left-clicking, then drag to rotate the object around a Pivot. The rotation aligns the selected vertex to face the direction of the Vertex closest to the mouse. The Snapping Vertex and Degree of rotation is displayed in the GUI.

Displays the length of the selected element. When vertices are selected, the distance between the vertices is displayed in the order selected. For edges, the length of all selected edges is displayed, and for faces, the length of all edges composing the selected faces is displayed. In the bottom right of the scene view, the total length is displayed. The ruler can be enabled or disabled in Preferences > UModeler X > Display > Ruler property.
The Misc group is a collection of tools with features that don't belong in any other group.

Modeling mode is the primary mode for editable meshes, and its primary function is to edit meshes. This mode is broken down into tools, which serve multiple functions, properties, which are detailed settings for the tools, and groups, which are groups of tools. note Element.​ In order to use a tool, you must select or use a 3D primitive called an Element. Elements are composed of Vertices, Edges, Faces, and Objects. A Vertex is a vertex of a 3D object, while an Edge represents a corner made up of two vertices. A Face is a surface filled by connecting three or more edges. UModelerX provides several tools for editing and creating vertices, edges, and faces. Moving, rotating, and resizing each element is the same as in the Unity Editor.

In order to use a tool, you must select or use a 3D primitive called an Element. Elements are composed of Vertices, Edges, Faces, and Objects. A Vertex is a vertex of a 3D object, while an Edge represents a corner made up of two vertices. A Face is a surface filled by connecting three or more edges.
The Element group is located at the top of Modeling Mode and is a collection of properties for each element (Vertex, Edge, Face, and Object). Each element has different visible properties.
The Primitive Shapes group is a collection of tools that allow you to create meshes of primitive shapes. For more information, see the Primitive Shapes group page.
The Drawing group is a collection of tools for creating planar shapes. For more information, see the Drawing group page.
The Selection group is a collection of tools related to the selection of elements (Vertex, Edge, Face, and Object). For more information, see the Selection Group page.

The Add group is a collection of tools that, when executed, will add each element (Vertex, Edge, Face). It mainly contains tools that either add selected elements or add elements defined in the tool. For more information, see the Add Group page.

The Remove group is a collection of tools that, when executed, remove each element (Vertex, Edge, Face). It usually contains tools that either delete selected elements or combine elements by the tool. For more information, see the Remove group page.
The Deform group is a collection of brush-like tools that apply deformations to surfaces. For more information, see the Deform group page.

The Surface group is a collection of tools for surfaces. It mainly contains vertex colors, material settings, and tools that can be used with the UV Editor. For more information, see the Surface group page.
The Misc group is a collection of functional tools that do not belong in any other group. For more information, see the Misc Groups page.
A Multiple Object group is a collection of tools that can be used with multiple UModeler X objects selected. For more information, see the Multiple Object Group page.

Unity's Grid/Incremental snap also applies to the Editable Mesh. Grid snap operates according to the size of Unity's grid. Incremental snap operates while pressing the Ctrl key on Windows and the Command key on MacOS. For more details, refer to the Unity manual on Grid snapping. Below are examples showing how Grid/Incremental snap is applied.
Primitive shape Grid/Incremental snap has been applied since UModeler X version 0.19.0.
Repeat Tool rerun a previously executed tool with the same settings.

Use Immediate mode tool. (ex. remove tool, duplicate tool) Select other elements to apply the same tool you used. Press the ; button on the keyboard to use the Repeat Tool. Previously used tool will be executed as is. note Immediate mode tool is a tool that executes immdeiately without displaying an additional settings inspector when the button is pressed. note Only the Bevel Tool is an exception, as it is not immediate mode tool but can be used by Repeat Tool.
A Multiple Objects group is a collection of tools that can be used with multiple UModeler X objects selected.
The Primitive Shapes group is a collection of tools for creating meshes of primitive shapes.

The Remove group is a collection of tools that, when executed, will remove each element (Vertex, Edge, Face). It mainly contains tools that either remove selected elements or merge elements by the tool.
The Selection group is a collection of tools related to the selection of each element (Vertex, Edge, Face, and Object).
The Surface group is a collection of tools for surfaces. It mainly contains vertex colors, material settings, and tools that can be used with the UV Editor.

documents.t: The Align Tool is a tool that Aligns the vertices of the selected elements within bounds.
Launch the Align Tool. Select the elements you want to align. Choose Alignment Axis and Alignment Direction. Click on Align button.
X, Y, or Z axis for alignment.
TowardsMin: Minimum location of the selected axis. TowardsMiddle: Middle location of the selected axis. TowardsMax: Maximum location of the selected axis
The All tool is a tool that selects all selected elements.
Select Vertices from the Select Top Elements. Run the All Tool. All vertices of the current object are selected.
Select an edge from the Select Top Element. Run the All Tools. All edges of the current object are selected.
Select the Face from the Select Top Element. Run the All Tool. All faces of the current object are selected.
The Bend Modifier is a modifier that allows you to bend objects. You can adjust the shape using properties such as the Axis to bend and Angle.
Click the Add Modifier button. Select the Bend modifier. Select the Axis to Bend in the Bend Axis Properties. Adjust the Angle to Bend in the Angel property. The object is now bend.
The property for the angle to be bent.
Property for the direction of the bend.
Property that sets the axis for the direction of the bend.
Property to set the reference for bending about the X axis.
Property that sets the Y axis to be bent by.
Property that sets the Z axis to be bent by.
Properties that allow you to limit the bend range.
Property that sets the limit range in the positive direction of the selected axis. The unit is meters. note Works when the Limit Effect property is enabled.
Property that sets the limit range in the negative direction of the selected axis. The unit is meters. note Works when the Limit Effect property is enabled.
Property that sets the position of the center point. note You can also change the Pivot property by moving the scene displayed gizmo.
A property that resets all properties.
The Bevel Tool is a tool that bevels selected elements.

Select a vertex. Run the Bevel Tool. Select Vertex from Bevel Type. note For a vertex, only Vertex type can be selected. Adjust the properties to the appropriate values. After adjusting the Properties, select the element, or press another tool to finalize.
Select an edge. Launch the Bevel tool. Under Bevel Type, select Vertex or Edge. Adjust to the appropriate value. After adjusting the properties, select the element, or press another tool to finish.

Select a face. Run the Bevel Tool. In the Bevel Type property, select either Vertex or Edge. Adjust to the appropriate value. After adjusting the properties, select the element, or use another tool to finish.
This property sets the type of element to be affected by the Bevel tool note For vertices, only the Vertex Type can be selected.
A property that affects only the vertices belonging to the selected element.
Properties that affect only edges belonging to the selected element.
Property that sets the length of the clipping.
This property sets the number of pieces that will be cut off.
This property sets the protrusion of the clipping.
Boolean Tool is a tool that allows you to glue two objects together, extract only the overlap, or subtract one object from another for a selected two objects.

Select two UModeler X objects. Run the Boolean tool in the Multiple Objects group. Select one of the Union, Intersection, or Subtraction buttons. The first selected object is assigned as A, the next selected object is assigned as B, and the order of A and B is important when using the Subtraction button. The result of the selection is created as a new object.
View the name of the object registered as Object A.
View the name of the object registered as Object B.

Combines two objects into a single object. The overlapping mesh is removed and a new object is created. note Different from the Combine Tool in the Multiple Objects group.​ Combine Tool simply combines two or more objects into a single object, while the Union in the Boolean Tool combines two objects into one, but removes the mesh of the overlapping parts. 📄️ Combine Tool

Combine Tool simply combines two or more objects into a single object, while the Union in the Boolean Tool combines two objects into one, but removes the mesh of the overlapping parts. 📄️ Combine Tool
documents.s: Different from the Combine Tool in the Multiple Objects group.

documents.t: Button to make two objects into a single object, leaving only the overlapping parts.
Button that creates a new object by subtracting Object B from Object A.
Button that creates a new object by subtracting Object A from Object B.
The Border Tool is a tool that selects all the edges of an object.
Change to the Edge Element state. Run the Border tool. All edge edges of the current object will be selected.
The Box tool is a tool for creating basic shaped boxes.
The basic shape creation tools in the Primitive Shapes group can create shapes in two ways. Click-Drag to create, edit Create and edit using One Click Build

Select the Box tool. Click and drag the mouse on the scene to create a base of the desired size. Once the base is created at the desired size, release the click and move the mouse up to create a mesh at the desired height. Once you have the desired height, click again to finish creating the mesh. Adjust the Box tool's properties and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue fine-tuning with the Box tool's properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.
documents.s: Create and edit by clicking and dragging

documents.t: Select the Box tool. Enter the desired value in the Properties of the Box tool. Press the One Click Build button to add the shape to the scene. Make any additional adjustments to the Box tool's properties and select the element, or use another tool to finish. note You can continue to refine the properties of the Box tool until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.
documents.s: One Click Build and Edit via Properties

documents.t: This property sets the width of the shape being created. In the direction corresponding to the Z axis relative to the object, in meters.
This property sets the vertical size of the generated shape. This is in the direction of the object's base, along the X-axis, and is measured in meters.
This property sets the height of the generated shape. This is in the direction corresponding to the Y axis, relative to the object, in meters.
This property sets the number of horizontal segments of the generated shape.
Property that sets the number of vertically split pieces of the generated shape.
This property sets the number of pieces that are split for the height of the generated shape.

The Bridge tool is a tool that creates faces between elements (Vertices, Edges) that are separated from each other. note The group of selected edges must not be more than two groups, and the number of edges in the two groups must be equal to each other.
Select the vertices you want to connect. Run the Bridge Tool. A face is created between the vertices you want to connect.
Select the edges you want to connect. Run the Bridge Tool. A face is created between the edges you want to connect.
The Capsule Tool is a tool for creating shapes that are capsule shaped.
The basic shape creation tools in the Primitive Shapes group can create shapes in two ways. Click-Drag to create, edit Create and edit using One Click Build

Select the Capsule Tool. Create a capsule sphere of the desired size by click-dragging the desired location in the scene. Once you have the desired size, release the click and move the mouse up to adjust the height of the capsule. When the desired height is reached, click again to finish creating the capsule. Adjust the Capsule Tool's properties and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue to fine-tune with the Capsule Tool's Properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.
documents.s: Create and edit by clicking and dragging

documents.t: select the Capsule tool. Enter the desired value in the properties of the Capsule Tool. Press the One Click Build button to add the shape to the scene. Make any additional adjustments to the Capsule Tool's properties and select the element, or press another tool to finalize. note You can continue to fine-tune with the Capsule Tool's Properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.
documents.s: One Click Build and Edit via Properties

documents.t: This property sets the radius size of the generated capsule.
This property sets the column height of the generated capsule.
This property sets the number of pieces the generated capsule is split for height.
This property sets the number of segments the generated capsule will be split into for the perimeter of the column portion.
This property sets the number of pieces that are split up and down for the spherical portion of the generated capsule.
This property allows you to choose how the mesh is displayed.
The Combine tool is a tool that creates multiple UModeler X objects into one object.
Select 2 or more UModeler X objects. Run the Combine Tool. The selected objects will become one object.
The Collapse tool is a tool that combines selected elements (Vertex, Edge, Face) at once. note Selected elements will be combined in groups that are connected to each other, not by distance.
Select one or more vertices. Run the Collapse tool. The selected Vertices groups will be merged together.
Select one or more edges. Run the Collapse tool. The selected Edges groups will be merged together.
Select one or more faces. Run the Collapse tool. the selected Face groups will be merged together.
The Combine Face Tool combines selected faces into a single face. caution Depending on the selected faces, the Combine Face Tool may generate a highly curved face, or may not work at all.
Select 2 or more faces. Run the Combine Face Tool. the selected faces will be combined into one face.
Cone Tool is a tool for creating shapes shaped like a cone.
The basic shape creation tools in the Primitive Shapes group can create shapes in two ways. Click-Drag to create, edit Create and edit using One Click Build

Select the Cone Tool. Create the base of the cone by click-dragging the desired location in the scene. Once the base is created at the desired size, release the click and move the mouse up to adjust the height of the cone. When the desired height is reached, click again to finish creating the cone. Adjust the Cone Tool's properties and select an element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue to fine-tune with the Cone Tool's Properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.
documents.s: Create and edit by clicking and dragging

documents.t: Select the Cone Tool. Enter the desired value in the properties of the Cone Tool. Press the One Click Build button to add the shape to the scene. Make any additional adjustments to the Cone Tool's properties and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue to fine-tune with the Cone Tool's Properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.
documents.s: One Click Build and Edit via Properties

The Connect tool is a tool that creates an edge that connects between selected elements (Vertex, Edge).
Select the vertices you want to connect. Run the Connect tool. An edge is created between the vertices you want to connect.
Select an edge to connect. Run the Connect tool. An edge is created between the edges you want to connect.
The Cylinder tool is a tool for creating basic shapes of cylinders.

Select the Cylinder tool. Click and drag the mouse on the scene to create a base of the desired size. Once the base is created at the desired size, release the click and move the mouse up to create a mesh at the desired height. When the desired height is reached, Click again to finish creating the mesh. Adjust the properties of the Cylinder tool and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue fine-tuning with the Cylinder tool's properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.

Custom Coordinate Tool is a tool for setting up Custom Coordinate System in UModelerX. note Custom Coordinate System You can check the Custom Coordinate System through the UModelerX Toolbar.

Select the Origin Point among the vertices of the chosen object. Select the X-Axis direction among the other vertices of the object. Select the Y-Axis direction among the other vertices of the object. Check if the Custom Coordinate System is correctly set in the UModelerX Coordinate System Toolbar. note If the x-axis or y-axis is not set correctly, the process may not proceed.
The Detach tool is used to detach only selected faces from the message, or to detach them from the object currently being edited and separate them into a new object.

The Detach tool is a tool that is applied directly according to the set properties, so you need to change the properties before executing it. tip The properties you change will remain the same until you change them again, so it's useful to change them to properties you use frequently. See how to use it according to the properties below.
note You can change properties in the Properties window that appears when you Alt+click on the Detach tool icon.
select a face. Run the Detach Tool. The selected faces are detached from the connected mesh.
select a face. Run the Detach Tool. The faces will detach, creating a new object with the selected faces.

The Decimate Modifier is a modifier for reducing the number of polygons in a model. note The Decimate modifier allows you to reduce the number of polygons in your model while maintaining as much detail as possible, which can improve mesh render times and overall performance. However, it should be set with the understanding that there may be significant changes in the appearance of the model depending on the properties set.
Press the Modifier Add Button. Select the Decimate Modifier. Adjust the Ratio property. The number of polygons in the model will decrease according to the adjusted Ratio property.
This property preserves the edges of faces and openings as much as possible.
Property for preserving surface curvature as much as possible. This is recommended to be enabled to preserve silhouettes.
This property allows vertices that are in the same location to be treated as the same vertex to avoid issues such as holes when reducing polygons.

A property that preserves the edges of the UVs that are the boundaries of the UVs and the corresponding edges of the model, keeping the UVs that touch the texture and consequently ensuring that the texture is well represented in the model. Only works when the Enable Smart Link property is enabled.
This property preserves edges that have the same UV. Only works when the Enable Smart Link property is enabled.
This property sets the maximum iteration count of the polygon reduction process.
This property sets the aggressiveness of the polygon reduction process. Higher values will remove more polygons, but the quality of the reduction may be lower.
A property for the ratio of the number of existing polygons. For example, a value of 0.5 for the Ratio property aims to reduce the number of polygons by 50% compared to the existing.
A wireframe preview of the polygon reduction result.

Run the Face Color tool. Enable the View Face Color property, which will display the object's face colors. Select the faces you want to apply the face color* to. Click on the Face Color property to change it to the desired color. Click the Apply Color button to apply the face color.

Face Normal tool adjusts the direction of face normals. The closer the normals align with the light direction, the brighter the surface appears. note For the Face Normal​ The Face Normal is the color information stored on a face.

Run the Face Normal tool. Click the Select Face Normals button to select the face whose face normals you want to rotate. Use the rotate gizmo to adjust the face normals.

The Free Form Deformaion (FFD) modifier is a modifier that uses a grid box surrounding a mesh and vertices that can be manipulated to deform the grid. note The Types of FFF Modifiers.​ There are three types of FFD Modifiers based on the number of manipulatable vertices. FFD 2x2x2 FFD 3x3x3 FFD 4x4x4
There are three types of FFD Modifiers based on the number of manipulatable vertices. FFD 2x2x2 FFD 3x3x3 FFD 4x4x4
Press the Add Modifier button. Select an FFD Modifier with the desired number of vertices. Click-Drag the vertices in the grid box. The mesh will deform smoothly.
The Flatten Brush tool is a brush-like tool that flattens surfaces.
Launch the Flatten Brush tool. Adjust the desired properties. Move the mouse cursor over the vertices of the object, then click-drag to organize the vertices.

This property determines the size of the brush's radius. The unit is meters. tip Use the keyboard shortcuts [ , ] , Shift+click-drag​ Hotkeys allow you to increase or decrease the Brush Radius property.

Flip tool reverses the direction of selected faces, adjusting their rendering status.
select the face you want to flip. Run the Flip Tool. The orientation of the selected faces has been reversed.
The Follow Tool is a tool that allows you to quickly create shapes by specifying an area.
Select the edges to be used as the Path, click the Follow Tool, and then select the face to be used as the Profile. This is how the shape is created.

documents.t: The Grow tool expands the area of the selected element and is selected. If no element is selected, or if there is no more area to expand, it will not work.
select one or more vertices. Run the Grow tool. the selected vertices will be expanded to select more area than.
Select one or more edges. Run the Grow tool. The selected edges will be expanded to select more area.
Select one or more faces. Run the Grow tool. the selected faces are expanded to select more areas than.
The Hotspot Texturing tool is a procedural tool designed for quick and efficient level, using designated textures.

Drag the Modular Texture you want to use from the Project Panel onto a mesh to apply it. Right-click in the Project Panel and create a new Hotspot Layout. Assign the Hotspot Layout 3-1. Open the Hotspot tool. 3-2. Assign the created Hotspot Layout to the Hotspot Object. 3-3. Click on the target area or activate the Hotspot Editor from the Editor to enable the Hotspot Editor. Click the gear icon in the top-right corner of the Hotspot Layout Editor and assign a texture to the Temporary Texture field. note Snap Type and Grid Snap Size​ Snap Type: Configues the snapping behavior of the working area. Grid Snap Size: Defines the size of the selectable area in pixel units, allowing precise adjustments for the texture. For this guide, set the Snap Type to UV and the Grid Snap Size to 1/256. note Layout Group​ New Layout: Divides the working area into segments. Edit Layout: Modifies the assigned segments. Remove Layout: Deletes incorrectly assigned segments. note What is DefaultMag?​ DefaultMag controls the scale factor between the texture size and the 3D world size. DefaultMag = 1: A 1x1 area in UV space corresponds to a 1x1 unit in the 3D world. DefaultMag > 1: The texture is enlarged. DefaultMag < 1: The texture is scaled down and applied more densely. tip Tips for Setting DefaultMag: Recommended range: 1~5. Avoid values that are too high (textures may appear blurry) or too low (textures may look overly dense). Adjust and test the value to find the optimal balance for your needs. Use New Layout feature to automatically align texture areas to match the mesh's scale changes.

Snap Type: Configues the snapping behavior of the working area. Grid Snap Size: Defines the size of the selectable area in pixel units, allowing precise adjustments for the texture. For this guide, set the Snap Type to UV and the Grid Snap Size to 1/256.
documents.s: Snap Type and Grid Snap Size

documents.t: New Layout: Divides the working area into segments. Edit Layout: Modifies the assigned segments. Remove Layout: Deletes incorrectly assigned segments.

DefaultMag controls the scale factor between the texture size and the 3D world size. DefaultMag = 1: A 1x1 area in UV space corresponds to a 1x1 unit in the 3D world. DefaultMag > 1: The texture is enlarged. DefaultMag < 1: The texture is scaled down and applied more densely.

Activate the UV Editor window. In the Unwrap Panel, ensure the mesh has no UVs. If UVs exist, select all and remove them by clicking the Cancel icon. tip Tip: Disable the "Auto Unwrap Shape" option in Preferences > Editable Mesh to prevent automatic UV Unwrapping for new shapes. Select the mesh, then navigate to Surface > Hotspot > Auto Hotspot in Build. Move the face to see procedural changes based on the assigned texture.

Select the mesh and navigate to Surface > Hotspot > Auto Hotspot Selected Face. After moving the face, textures may stretch or distort. Use Auto Hotspot Selected Faces again after each transformation. This applies only to selected faces.

In the Hotspot Layout Editor window, select Edit Layout. Click a face, then set its Layout Name in the Tool Properties window. In this guide, we name it "test". In the Inspector, go to the UModeler X Component and click Surface > Hotspot. In Tool Properties, select the previously created layout under Selected Layout. Click Fit Selected Hotspot Face. Confirm that the selected face displays correctly in the viewport.

A. Auto Hotspot in Build: Automatically updates texture regions in real-time when moving mesh faces. B. Auto Hotspot Selected Faces: Manually updates texture regions for selected faces. C. Fit Selected Hotspot Faces: Adjusts textures precisely using assigned layouts.

The Insert Vertex tool adds a vertex over the desired edge.

Yellow: Centered on the edge Green: Non-center position on the edge note This method is not exposed in the editor.

The Inset tool is a tool that creates new faces based on the selected faces as if they were inset. note The Inset tool only works with faces.
select a face. Run the Inset Tool. Adjust the properties to the appropriate values. After adjusting the properties, select the element, or use another tool to finalize.

documents.t: Launch the Inset Tool. Select the face you want to apply the Inset Tool to. If you want to apply it to multiple faces, you can hold down Shift and select additional faces. This property controls the size of the face generated by the Inset Tool. note When negative, the face is generated to the inside of the face, and when positive, the face is generated to the outside of the face.

The Invert tool selects the inverted portion of the selected element.
Select one or more vertices. Run the Invert tool. The inverted parts of the selected vertices are selected.
Select one or more edges. Run the Invert tool. The inverted parts of the selected edges are selected.

The Isolate tool is a tool that selects the selected element and its connected parts together.
Select one or more vertices. Run the Isolate Tool. All vertices up to the elements connected by a face are selected.
Select one or more edges. Run the Isolate tool. All edges up to the connected element are selected.
Select one or more faces. Run the Isolate tool. All faces up to the connected element are selected.
A Knife Tool is a tool that connects an edge or vertex to an edge.

Launch the Knife Tool. Click on the edge or vertex that you want to use as a starting point. Create edges by Click on other edges or vertices that you want to connect to create the desired shape. Continue to Click on other edges or vertices to connect them. note Mouse cursor dot color and snapping​ The color of the dot on your mouse cursor tells you which element the point you're about to click is on. Snapping also allows you to Click exactly at a specific point to connect. Left: Point on edge, Right: point on face The color on the edge is green, as shown above. If it is on a face, where the Knife Tool does not work, it will be gray. Left: Points on vertices, Right: Point at the center of an edge If it is on a vertex and in the center of an edge, it will be colored yellow and the mouse cursor will snap.

The Linear Array Modifier is a modifier that duplicates selected elements (Vertex, Edge, Face) and arranges them in a linear direction. note This feature is exclusive to UModeler X Plus
Click the Add Modifier button. Select the Linear Array modifier. Choose Length Type. Adjust the values as needed.

This determines the position of the last object in the array. There are two types: Total and Interval. Total: The last object is positioned at the distance specified by the Total value. Interval: The last object is positioned based on the angle and batch count.
The array follows the 3D direction vector originating from the pivot of the original element.

The Local Settings Tool is a tool used to manage and adjust the local settings of selected objects. It provides the ability to quickly change certain properties of an object, recalculate the state of an object, and more, with additional features planned for the future.
Launch the Local Settings Tool. Select the desired property. The feature corresponding to the selected property will be applied to the currently selected object.
This property recalculates the object's tangent vectors. Use this when you are having trouble applying a normal map, or when you need accurate normals while editing a mesh.

When the option is enabled, UModelerX data and mesh information are saved in a subfolder under the scene file. If the option is disabled, the data is stored directly in the scene file. For large meshes, saving them in a folder is recommended.

select 2 or more adjacent faces in the desired direction. Run the Loop tool. note Shortcut for the Loop tool on faces. After selecting the faces, Shift+Double-Click the faces in the desired direction. the faces in the direction of travel of the selected faces will be selected.

documents.t: The Reset X Form Tool in the Multiple Objects Group is a tool that resets the Position, Rotation, and Scale values of the transforms of multiple selected objects. It is the same as the Reset X Form Tool in the Misc Group, except that it can be applied to multiple objects at once. note How it differs from the Reset X Form Tool in the Misc Group​ The Reset X Form Tool in the Misc Group differs in that it can only reset the Position, Rotation, and Scale values for the one model that is selected and being edited. 📄️ Reset X Form Tool

documents.t: The Pinch Brush tool is a brush-like tool that gathers the gaps between vertices. The result is a pointed or sharpened shape.
Launch the Pinch Brush tool. Adjust the desired properties. Move the mouse cursor over the vertices of the object, then click and drag to bring the vertices together.

This property determines the radius size of the brush. The unit is meters. tip Use the keyboard shortcuts [ , ] , Shift+click-drag​ Hotkeys allow you to increase or decrease the Brush Radius property.
Hotkeys allow you to increase or decrease the Brush Radius property.
A Graph Shape property that determines the shape of the brush. It can be edited by clicking on the graph next to Fall Off.
The Pipe tool is a tool that creates a cylinder with a hole in the center.
The basic shape creation tools in the Primitive Shapes group can create shapes in two ways. click-drag to create, edit Create and edit using One Click Build

Select the Pipe tool. Click and drag the mouse in the scene to create the outside of the base with the desired outside radius size. Once the shape is created at the desired size, release the click and move the mouse to the inside of the shape to generate a mesh at the desired inside radius size. note If you move the mouse outward rather than inward, the initially created radius will be inward and the area you move the mouse over will be outward. When the desired bottom is reached, click again and move the mouse up to generate a mesh at the desired height. When the desired height is reached, click again to finish creating the mesh. Adjust the properties of the Pipe tool and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue to refine the properties of the Pipe tool until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.

documents.t: Select the Pipe tool. Enter the desired value in the Pipe tool's properties. Press the One Click Build button to add a shape to the scene. Make any additional adjustments to the Pipe tool's properties and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue to tweak the properties of the Pipe tool until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.

documents.t: This property sets the radius size of the shape being created based on its center. When creating via Click-Drag, this is the property at the time of the first Click.
This property sets the radius size of the shape being created based on its center. When creating via Click-Drag, this is the property on the second Click.
This property sets the height of the generated shape. When creating via Click-Drag, this property is set on the third Click.
Property that sets the number of pieces the perimeter surface of the generated shape will be split into.
Property that sets the number of segments for the height of the generated shape.

Pivot Tool is a tool for setting the pivot location of an object, allowing the pivot to be changed to the object's Center, Top Center, Bottom Center, or the current location of the gizmo. note Pivot.​ Pivot is the central point of reference when adjusting the position, rotation, and scale of an object. It serves as the origin within the object, defining the location of each element in the object's space relative to the position of the gizmo. note Checking the Pivot Position​ To ascertain the exact position of the pivot, the gizmo display reference in the Unity Editor must be set to Pivot. This setting makes the gizmo represent the pivot location of the object, allowing you to verify the pivot's position as the center point of the object. When using the Pivot Tool in UModeler X, clicking the attribute button instantly switches the gizmo reference to Pivot, making it easy to check the current pivot location.

Pivot is the central point of reference when adjusting the position, rotation, and scale of an object. It serves as the origin within the object, defining the location of each element in the object's space relative to the position of the gizmo.

To ascertain the exact position of the pivot, the gizmo display reference in the Unity Editor must be set to Pivot. This setting makes the gizmo represent the pivot location of the object, allowing you to verify the pivot's position as the center point of the object. When using the Pivot Tool in UModeler X, clicking the attribute button instantly switches the gizmo reference to Pivot, making it easy to check the current pivot location.
A button that sets the pivot location to the Top Center of the object.
A button that sets the pivot location to the Center of the object.
A button that sets the pivot location to the Bottom Center of the object.

A button that sets the pivot location to the current location of the gizmo displayed in the scene. After moving the displayed gizmo to the desired location, clicking the Gizmo Location button sets the object's pivot to the new location of the chosen gizmo.

Gizmo Local Position shows the location of the gizmo within the object's local coordinate system. It displays the relative position of how far the currently displayed gizmo is from the object's pivot.

Gizmo World Position shows the location of the gizmo within the scene's world coordinate system. It displays the relative position of how far the currently displayed gizmo is from the world's origin, regardless of the object's local transformations.
Setting the pivot position using the Gizmo Location button after moving the gizmo
The Push modifier is a modifier used to push faces in the normal or opposite direction.
Press the Add Modifier button. Select the Push Modifier. Change the Push Size property. the faces will be spaced apart and become larger or smaller.
Property for how far apart the faces should be. If 0, there is no change.

The PushPull tool allows you to extrude a selected face outward or push it inward along its normal direction. With this tool, you can push or pull faces of various shapes, including circles, rectangles, and abstract polygons. note This feature is exclusive to UModeler X Plus
Run the PushPull tool. Select the face you want to PushPull. Drag the selected face along its normal direction. Release the left mouse button (LMB) when the extrusion is complete.
This property adjusts the height of the push/pull action.
The Radial Array Tool duplicates selected elements (Vertex, Edge, Face) and arranges them in a circular direction. note This feature is exclusive to UModeler X Plus
Select the element to copy. Run the Radial Array Tool. Choose Array Type. Select Length Type. Choose Rotate Axis. Adjust the values as needed.
Specifies the element types affected by the Radial Array Tool.
Select a face. Run the Radial Array Tool. A new element array will be created within the connected mesh from the selected element.

documents.t: Select a face. Run the Radial Array Tool. A new independent object array will be created from the current mesh.

documents.t: This determines the position of the last object in the array. There are two types: Total and Interval. Total: The last object is positioned at the distance specified by the Total value. Interval: The last object is positioned based on the angle and batch count.
This defines the axis around which the original model rotates. You can choose between the X, Y, or Z axis.
This is the distance between the original model and the axis of rotation.
This is the reference value for rotation when creating an array of duplicates.
When checked, duplicates are rotated clockwise. When unchecked, they are rotated counterclockwise.
When checked, the duplicated elements maintain the same orientation as the original element. When unchecked, the duplicated elements will face the center of rotation.
Sets the number of elements or objects to be created (from 2 to 1000).
Properties that allow you to set how faces are selected.
The Radial Array Modifier is a modifier that duplicates selected elements (Vertex, Edge, Face) and arranges them in a circular direction. note This feature is exclusive to UModeler X Plus
Click the Add Modifier button. Select the Radial Array modifier. Choose Length Type. Choose Rotate Axis. Adjust the values as needed.

This determines the position of the last object in the array. There are two types: Total and Interval. Total: The last object is positioned at the distance specified by the Total value. Interval: The last object is positioned based on the angle and batch count.
This defines the axis around which the original model rotates. You can choose between the X, Y, or Z axis.
This is the distance between the original model and the axis of rotation.
This is the reference value for rotation when creating an array of duplicates.
When checked, duplicates are rotated counterclockwise. When unchecked, they are rotated clockwise.
When checked, the duplicated elements maintain the same orientation as the original element. When unchecked, the duplicated elements will face the center of rotation.
Sets the number of elements or objects to be created (from 2 to 1000).

The Relax Brush tool is a brush-like tool that organizes the spacing between vertices while maintaining the existing shape. note Differences from the Smooth Brush tool​ While the Relax Brush tool more or less keeps the existing shape while adjusting the spacing, the Smooth Brush tool smooths while changing the shape.
While the Relax Brush tool more or less keeps the existing shape while adjusting the spacing, the Smooth Brush tool smooths while changing the shape.

The Rectangle tool is a tool that creates rectangular planar meshes.
The Rectangle tool can create rectangular planes in two ways. Click-Drag to create, edit Create and edit using One Click Build

Select the Rectangle tool. Click and drag the mouse in the scene to create a plane of the desired size. Once the plane is the desired size, click Finish to finish creating the mesh. Adjust the properties of the Rectangle tool and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue fine-tuning with the Rectangle tool's properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.

documents.t: This property sets the width of the shape being created. In the direction corresponding to the Z axis relative to the object, in meters.
This property sets the vertical size of the generated shape. This is in the direction corresponding to the X-axis, relative to the object, and is measured in meters.

The Ring tool is a tool that selects elements parallel to the selected element.
Select one or more edges. Run the Ring Tool. Edges in a direction parallel to the selected edges are selected.

note The Ring tool only works with faces consisting of 4 edges. select 2 or more faces adjacent to each other. Run the Ring tool. Faces in a direction parallel to the direction of travel of the selected faces will be selected.
note You can change the properties in the properties window that appears when you Alt+Click on the Ring tool icon.
The At One Go property is a property that allows you to select all edges and faces at once based on the Ring tool selection criteria. Edge Face
The Grow property is a property that allows selection in a way that increases the range each time the Ring tool icon is clicked. note Faces are not subject to the Grow property.
The Reset X Form Tool is a tool that will Reset the Position, Rotation, and Scale values of the transform of the selected object.
Launch the Reset X Form Tool. Click on the desired property button. You will see that the values of the Transform component are reset according to the selected properties.
This property will Reset All of the object's Position, Rotation, and Scale values.
Property that resets the Position Value of an object.
Property that resets the object's Rotation Value.
Property that resets the object's Scale Value.
The Room tool is a tool for creating room-shaped models.
The basic shape creation tools in the Primitive Shapes group can create shapes in two ways. Click-Drag to create, edit Create and edit using One Click Build

Select the Room tool. Create a Bottom of the desired size by click-dragging it with the mouse anywhere in the scene. Once the base is created at the desired size, release the click and move the mouse up to generate a mesh at the desired height. When you reach the desired height, click again to finish creating the mesh. Adjust the thickness of the wall by adjusting the Thickness in the Room tool's properties. If you enable the XRay Mode, the face will appear translucent, making it easier to adjust. Adjust the remaining properties of the Box Tool and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue to fine-tune with the Room Tool's Properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.

This property sets the height of the generated room shape. It is in the direction corresponding to the Y axis relative to the object's base, with units in meters.

The Separate Parts Tool creates new objects by separating disconnected parts from the selected object.
Select 1 UModelerX object. Run the Separate Parts Tool. Disconnected parts are separated into new objects.

The Shell modifier is a modifier that can generate thickness. You can generate thickness by expanding or contracting the original mesh in the normal direction, and you can also add a face to the cross-section of the generated thickness.
Press the Add Modifier button. Select the Shell Modifier. Change the Inner Size property or Outer Size property. the thickness has been created.
The separation distance of the faces facing inward, the opposite direction of the normal direction.
The separation distance of the faces facing the outward direction from the normal direction.
A property used to divide the generated faces in cross-sections of the thickness. note If the original mesh is not perforated, there is no change in the properties because no thickness is generated.
A property that allows you to see the wireframe result of the modifier, so you can see the current state of the element.
The Shrink tool is a tool that shrinks an area on selected elements. It does not work if there is no element selected
select one or more vertices. Run the Shrink Tool. The selected vertex area will be shrunk and selected. If there is not enough range for the selected faces, they will be deselected.
Select one or more edges. Run the Shrink Tool. The selected edges will be shrunk and selected. If the selected faces do not have enough range, they will be deselected.
Select one or more faces. Run the Shrink Tool. The selected faces will be shrunk and selected. If there is not enough range in the selected faces, they will be deselected.
The Slice Cut tool creates a virtual plane and generates edges on elements intersecting with it.
Select the Slice Cut tool. Move or rotate the gizmo to position the activated translucent plane where you want the edges to be created. Press the "Cut" button to generate the edges.
This property sets the position of the virtual plane.
Property that sets the rotation of the virtual plane.
Properties that allow you to select how the mesh is displayed.
Property to reset the position and rotation of the virtual plane.
Property that runs the Slice Cut tool with the current virtual plane state.
From version 0.18.0, new features such as View Cut, Action After Cut, and Angle Snap have been added.
A feature that creates a virtual plane aligned with the camera direction by dragging the mouse.

Defines the action to be taken after making a cut. Split Only: Cuts based on the virtual plane. Remove Above: Removes the part above the virtual plane and fills the cut surface. Remove Below: Removes the part below the virtual plane and fills the cut surface.
While holding down the Ctrl key and dragging the mouse, the virtual plane snaps to the view based on the rotation value of Incremental Snapping in the Unity editor.

The Spiral Stair Tool is a tool for creating shapes in the form of spiral staircases.
The basic shape creation tools in the Primitive Shapes group can create shapes in two ways. Click-Drag to create, edit Create and edit using One Click Build

Select the Spiral Stair tool. Create a circle of the desired size by clicking and dragging it to the desired location in the scene. Once it is the size you want, release the click and move the mouse to create a mesh with the desired stair width. Then click again and move the mouse up to generate a mesh at the desired height. Once you have the desired height, click again to finish creating the mesh. Adjust the height of each step by adjusting the Step Height among the properties of the Spiral Stair tool. The value of Step Height determines the number of steps in the staircase. Adjust the remaining properties of the Spiral Stair Tool and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue to fine-tune with the Spiral Stair Tool's Properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.

documents.t: This property sets the distance from the center of the spiral staircase to the inside of the staircase. In other words, this property sets the inside radius of the stairs.
This property sets the width of the generated stairs.
This property sets the overall height of the generated staircase.
Property that sets how much the entire staircase is rotated.
This property sets how much the spiral staircase is rotated. A value of 360 means that the beginning and end of the spiral stair will be exactly connected.
This property sets the height of one step in the staircase that is generated. The value determines the number of steps in the staircase, which affects the number of curved surfaces.
This property allows you to choose how the mesh is displayed.

The Subdivide modifier is a modifier that divides the current face into quarters while simultaneously smoothing out bends. note The Smoothing Groups property of the Face Element Group increases the actual number of faces, rather than just making it look like the faces are connected.

Press the Add Modifier button. Select the Subdivide modifier. In the Subdivision Level properties, select the Button for the desired step. caution Since this will divide the entire face into 4 parts per step, it is recommended that you start with a lower step, as the number of steps in the Subdivision Level property can cause optimization issues with 3D objects due to the large number of steps, as well as momentary editor slowdowns. faces are added and bends are smoothed out.
Property for the Subdivide Level. For each step, the number of faces is quadrupled and the bends are smoothed.
Example Subdivision Level 0 Example Subdivision Level 1 Example Subdivision Level 2

None​ Edge Only​ This property determines the bend without distinguishing between corners and edges. As a result, all vertices are smoothly represented. Edge And Corner​ This property determines the bend by distinguishing between vertices and edges.

This property sets the bending method for stretched UVs. None: Smooth interpolation across all faces. Corners Only: Sharpens only the corners. Corners Plus1: Linear interpolation for both edges and corners. Corners Plus2: Sharpen edges and corners, while extending sharpness to adjacent areas. Boundaries: Sharpens all boundaries. All: Applies bilinear interpolation to all surfaces. note This does not work if the UV is not unfolded. info Even if the UV is not stretched, it will have automatically generated UV texture coordinates based on the object's spatial coordinates, normal orientation. The image below is an example of how the UV changes based on each property.

A property that automatically applies a Smoothing Group to faces added by the Subdivision Level, making the surface appear smoother. tip Since increasing the value of Subdivision Level results in more polygons, it is a good idea to optimize by looking at the representation level with the Auto Smoothing Group property enabled and increasing the value of Subdivision Level.
A wireframe preview of the subdivided result.

The Subdivide Tool is a tool for quartering faces. If no faces are selected, it will quarter all faces to smooth out bends, and if specific faces are selected, it will quarter only the selected faces without deformation. caution Running the Subdivide Tool will divide the entire face of the selected object into quarters, so be careful when running it as it may cause optimization issues with 3D objects due to the large number of faces, momentary editor slowdowns, etc.. tip Subdivide Modifier​ Using the Subdivide Tool can lead to inefficient modeling because it is applied directly to the underlying mesh. Working through the Subdivide modifier (not a tool) allows you to model more efficiently because it allows you to apply deformations to the model while preserving the original mesh. 📄️ Subdivide Modifier

Using the Subdivide Tool can lead to inefficient modeling because it is applied directly to the underlying mesh. Working through the Subdivide modifier (not a tool) allows you to model more efficiently because it allows you to apply deformations to the model while preserving the original mesh. 📄️ Subdivide Modifier
Run the Subdivide Tool. the entire face will be quartered and additional faces will be created.

documents.t: Select the face. Run the Subdivide Tool. The selected face is quartered and an additional face is created.

documents.t: The Target Weld tool is used to drag selected vertices and weld them to a specific vertex.

Select the Target Weld tool. Click-Drag the vertices you want to weld. With the red guide attached to the mouse cursor, move the cursor to the vertex you want to weld. When the guide turns green, release the Click. The selected vertices will be moved and joined together.

Select Torus Tools. Click and drag the mouse in the scene to create a shape with the desired radius size. Once the shape is created at the desired size, release the Click and move the mouse up and down to create a mesh at the desired thickness. When the desired thickness is reached, Click again to finish creating the mesh. Adjust the Torus tool's properties and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue fine-tuning with the Torus tool's properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.

Property that sets the radius size for the thickness of the generated shape.
Property that sets the number of surface segments of the circle that are sections of the generated shape.
Property that sets the number of surface segments around the perimeter of the ring of the generated shape.

The Unmark UV Seam tool is a tool that unmarks a cut line set by the Mark UV Seam tool. note To Mark UV Seam.​ Since the UV Seam is not actually a cut edge of the mesh, you must have the Display UVSeam property of the edge Element group enabled in order to visually see it.
Since the UV Seam is not actually a cut edge of the mesh, you must have the Display UVSeam property of the edge Element group enabled in order to visually see it.

With the edge selected, enable the Display UVSeam property of the Element group. Select the edge you want to unmark. Run the Unmark UV Seam tool. The selected edge has been released from the cut line.

The UV Param tool allows you to adjust how textures are displayed on selected faces by transforming UV coordinates using properties such as position, rotation, scale, and tiling. note In the UV Editor window, if there are unwrapped faces, you need to select them and cancel the unwrapping of the selected ones before applying the UV Param function.
Select the faces you want to modify. Choose the UV Param Tool. Adjust shifting, scaling, and rotating properties in the Tool Properties panel.
Properties that allow you to set how faces are selected.
Increases or decreases the size of the texture.
Sets the number of times the texture repeats along the X and Y axes.
Selects faces with modified UV Param values.
Resets the UV Param values to their defaults.

The Vertex Color Brush tool is a brush-like tool that applies vertex color to vertices. note For the Vertex Color​ The Vertex Color is the color information stored on a vertex. Colors between vertices are automatically interpolated, and can be used for a variety of purposes.
The Vertex Color is the color information stored on a vertex. Colors between vertices are automatically interpolated, and can be used for a variety of purposes.

Run the Vertex Color Brush tool. Enable the View Vertex Color property, which will display the object's vertex colors. Click on the Brush Color property to change it to the desired color. Move the mouse cursor over the vertices of the object, then Click-Drag to paint the vertex color.
Property that displays the object's vertex color.
Property that allows you to specify the vertex color.
Properties that control the size and intensity of the brush.

This property selects what the brush size is based on. Pixel This property determines the size of the brush in pixels. You can set the size in the Brush Radius Pixel property. Distance This property determines the size of the brush relative to its size in the world. You can set the size in the Brush Radius Distance property. Distance Centimeter Determines the size of the brush relative to its size on the world. The unit is centimeters. You can set the size in the **Brush Radius Distance property.
This property sets the size of the brush relative to its worldly size. Available only when the Size Type property is set to Distance, Distance Centimeter.
This property sets the size of the brush in pixels. This property is only available when the Size Type property is set to Pixel.

A Graph Type property that determines the shape of the brush. It can be edited by clicking on the graph next to Fall Off. Fall Off Shape Example​ Here is an example of how the Fall Off shape changes the appearance of the selection.

The Vertex Color tool is a tool that applies a vertex color to selected vertices. note For the Vertex Color​ The Vertex Color is the color information stored on a vertex. Colors between vertices are automatically interpolated, and can be used for a variety of purposes.
The Vertex Color is the color information stored on a vertex. Colors between vertices are automatically interpolated, and can be used for a variety of purposes.

Run the Vertex Color tool. Enable the View Vertex Color property, which will display the object's vertex colors. Select the vertices you want to apply the vertex color to. Click on the Vertex Color property to change it to the desired color. Click the Apply Color button to apply the vertex color.
Property that displays the object's vertex color.
Property that allows you to specify the vertex color.
Properties that allow you to set how vertices are selected. 📄️ Backface Select 📄️ Camera Based Select
The Weld tool is a tool that joins selected vertices that are within a distance of a value set in the properties.

Select 2 or more vertices. Run the Weld tool. Enter the desired distance in the Distance property. Vertices whose distance between them is less than or equal to the value entered in the Distance property will be joined. Select the element, or use another tool to finalize.
This property allows you to set the distance between vertices to be merged.
An Object is an element that is used to leave an edit state. You can change to the Object state by pressing Shift+4, or by using the buttons at the top of the scene.
The modifier system allows for non-destructive transformations of the original model. This system enables efficient modeling as it allows modifications to be made while preserving the original model.
Modifiers can accumulate editing results through a history called a modifier stack, allowing for multiple modifiers to be applied sequentially. Also, specific modifiers can be toggled on and off.

The names of modifiers are determined at the time of creation based on their functions, and they can be changed to any desired name as needed. Double-click on the name part of the modifier to change it, then press Enter or click outside the text input area to complete the name change. tip By changing the name of the modifier to reflect its purpose, you can identify the purpose without having to check the modifier properties while working.
Modifiers are activated by default upon creation. To deactivate them, you can uncheck the checkbox next to the modifier name.

You can change the position of a modifier by clicking and dragging it to the desired location. note Modifiers cannot be moved below the source mesh, and the position of the source mesh cannot be changed.

The Combine Modifiers button reflects the results of the currently applied modifiers into the original mesh. When combining, the modifiers below the selected one are merged together. If you combine modifiers, the changes are applied to the source mesh, and the involved modifiers are removed. caution This action is difficult to undo, which may decrease work efficiency due to its irreversible nature.
You can add the desired modifiers through the Add Modifier button.
You can delete the selected modifier using the Delete Modifier button. note If you want to disable rather than delete, simply uncheck the checkbox.
📄️ Bend Modifier 📄️ Subdivide Modifier 📄️ Shell Modifier 📄️ Mirror Modifier 📄️ FFD Modifier 📄️ Push Modifier 📄️ Decimate Modifier 📄️ Linear Array Modifier 📄️ Radial Array Modifier

With UModeler X's Painting Mode, you can experience near-perfect painting features, from adjusting brush properties to editing layers and even mask effects. Paint directly on 3D models and check the results in real time. Now, you can also create textures directly in Unity.

A texture is an image used to express the details of a 3D model's surface. Textures can be applied to the whole or specific parts of a model through materials, and they are assigned to the model through the process of allocating materials. UModeler X allows you to create such textures directly through its built-in paint mode, and the key features are as follows
The painting mode of UModeler X is specially designed to help quickly and easily edit textures in both the 2D editor and 3D scene view.
documents.s: Supports both 3D Scene View and 2D Editor

documents.t: When painting colors, you can proceed by dividing the process into layers, such as sketching and coloring. There are transparent layers and layers that are already painted. Layers cannot affect other layers, but they influence the color of the model as they overlap. When layers overlap, you can set how they will overlap. You can set modes such as becoming brighter as they overlap and becoming darker as they overlap, which are called layer blending modes.

It supports the Paint layer for direct coloring with a brush, the Fill layer for covering the entire model, the Sticker layer for attaching images like stickers to the surface, and the Mask layer that can be used with these layers, allowing for a rich painting effect.
documents.s: Supports Paint, Fill, Sticker, and Mask Layers

documents.t: Through the Map Source, it is possible to paint not only colors but also various materials such as metallicity, shading, and roughness etc,. This allows you to paint the smoothness and roughness, and you can make it shine by painting glowing colors.

Textures use RGB channels to represent colors, with an additional value (Alpha) for transparency. Various colors are created by the intensity of each channel and combined into a single texture. The created texture is applied to the material and used as the model's color through the shader. The painting mode of UModeler X also supports the ability to edit these color values separately by channel, allowing for a variety of effects with a smaller number of textures.

If you connect UModeler X with a computer where Stable Diffusion WebUI is installed, you can directly map AI-generated images onto 3D models placed in the scene view based on prompts, the depth map and the input image created in the scene view. Moreover, you can easily and quickly obtain the desired results by incorporating AI-generated images with the layers in the painting mode.

Prepare an Editable Mesh model. Create a 3D model through the modeling mode of UModeler X, or convert an already created 3D mesh into an Editable Mesh using UModelerize. Select the Painting 3D tab. If it is not unwrapped, perform unwrapping to generate UV coordinates. UV Coordinates In 3D modeling, UV coordinates are used to map a 2D texture onto the surface of a 3D object. Here, U and V represent the axes of the 2D texture space, linking each point of the 3D model to a specific location on the texture. Through this mapping, detailed images, patterns, or colors can be accurately applied to the surface of the 3D model. Since UV coordinates align every point of the 3D model with the correct position on the texture, it is necessary to generate UV coordinates in advance through the unwrapping function so that the colors painted in painting mode are recorded on the texture. To start painting, at least one of the model's faces must be unfolded into UV coordinates using the tools in the unwrap group within the UV Editor. Also, for basic shapes, please check if the Auto Unwrap Shape property is activated in the Preference window. If this property is activated, UVs are already created when the basic shape is generated, allowing you to start painting immediately without the need for separate unwrapping work. Specify the properties for the material to be painted on. Startup Resolution : This property allows you to select the texture resolution for painting. It can be changed during painting. Startup Material Template : This property sets the predefined map source that will be used for painting. Startup Background Color : This property sets the background color that will be the base during painting. It can be changed during painting. Click Start Painting and begin painting

The painting mode of UModeler X uses a separate material designed for painting mode, allowing you to paint directly on the model you are currently working on. Therefore, to apply the image created in painting mode to the actual model, the following steps are necessary Click the Export All button at the bottom of the Map Source group to export the results drawn on the selected Map Source as a .png file. In the image below, you can see the result colored on the Albedo map source being exported. Set the exported texture in the appropriate slots such as Albedo, Metallic, Normal, etc., of the material used in modeling mode. In the image below, it shows assigning the texture exported from painting mode to the Albedo map of the material.
documents.s: Apply the texture worked on in painting mode.

documents.t: The Painting mode is used for coloring models, allowing the expression of colors and the creation of textures through the use of layers and brushes.
To use the Painting mode, you must first go through the setup process.
This property is displayed if the model does not have UVs unwrapped. If the UVs have been edited in the UV Editor, this property will not be displayed.

This is a property for selecting the material to be used for painting. Startup Resolution : This property allows you to select the texture resolution for painting. It can be changed during the painting process. Startup Material Template : This property is for setting predefined map sources to be used in painting. Startup Background Color : This property allows you to set the base color that will serve as the background during painting. It can be changed during the painting process.
The Painting 2D tool is an editor-style tool that synchronizes with the painting mode.
The Material group in Painting mode is a collection of properties related to selecting the material for painting or to the representation of materials in the scene.

The Layer group in Painting mode is a collection of tools for managing and editing layers, along with a display of the layers themselves. Layer Mask : This is a feature that masks a specific area of a layer. Group layers : This is a type of layer that integrates layers into a hierarchical structure for management. Paint Layers : This is a layer that allows coloring with a brush applied with color or an image to the map source. Fill layers : This type of layer applies an image across the whole map source, effectively covering the entire 3D model. Sticker Layers : This is a type of layer that represents sticking an image onto the surface.
The Properties group is an area where the content changes depending on the selected tool or layer, displaying properties related to the selected feature.
The Map Source group is a collection of properties for setting the texture's resolution, the map source's format, and managing map sources, including adding and deleting them.
A Group layer is a layer of properties that manages layers together.

The Stair Tool is a tool for creating stair-like shapes.
The basic shape creation tools in the Primitive Shapes group can create shapes in two ways. Click-Drag to create, edit Create and edit using One Click Build

Select the Stair Tool. Click and drag the mouse on the scene to create a staircase of the desired size. Once the base is created at the desired size, release the click and move the mouse up to create a mesh at the desired height. When you reach the desired height, click again to finish creating the mesh. Adjust the height of each step by adjusting the Step Height among the properties of the Stair tool. The value of Step Height determines the number of steps in the staircase. Adjust the remaining properties of the Stair Tool and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue to fine-tune with the Stair Tool's Properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.
documents.s: Create and edit by clicking and dragging

documents.t: Select the Stair tool. Enter the desired value in the properties of the Stair Tool. Click the One Click Build button to add the shape to the scene. Make any additional adjustments to the Stair Tool's properties and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue to fine-tune with the Stair Tool's Properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.

documents.t: This property sets the width of the generated stair.
This property sets the overall height of the generated stair model.
This property sets the depth of the generated stairs. Lower values make the staircase steeper, higher values make it gentler.

If checked, the entire stair model will be rotated 90 degrees, and the meaning of the Width and Depth properties will be reversed.

The Map Source Group is a collection of properties for managing map sources, such as adding and deleting map sources, setting the resolution of the texture, the format of the map source, and more. info Map Source​ In UModelerX's painting mode, the concept of 'map source' refers to individual characteristics that make up a material, such as metallicity, color, roughness, etc. For example, in the Standard Material of Built-in RP project, the Main Maps group's Albedo, Metallic, Normal Map, Height Map, Occlusion, etc., correspond to the map sources. By utilizing map sources, you can represent multiple material properties on a single texture.

In UModelerX's painting mode, the concept of 'map source' refers to individual characteristics that make up a material, such as metallicity, color, roughness, etc. For example, in the Standard Material of Built-in RP project, the Main Maps group's Albedo, Metallic, Normal Map, Height Map, Occlusion, etc., correspond to the map sources. By utilizing map sources, you can represent multiple material properties on a single texture.
A list of map sources currently being applied to the material.
This property sets the resolution of the texture.

This property sets the format of the selected map source. sRGB This property represents the map source color using the sRGB color space. RGB8 Property that represents the color of the map source using the 8-bit RGB color space. L8 A property that represents the map source value using an 8-bit grayscale.
This property sets the name of the shader variable that will be applied to the selected map source.
This property sets which of the texture's RGB channels the selected map source should be included in.

These are buttons marked with + and - symbols. You can add a new map source or remove the selected map source.
Export the colored results of the selected map source as .PNG or .TIFF files. Export All and Export a channel are exported as .PNG, while Export a channel with layers is exported in .TIFF format.

Map Sources : This is a property that only shows results from a specific map source. This will be displayed differently depending on the map source set. Albedo Metallic Smoothness Normal and more Mask : Property that displays the layer mask of the currently selected layer. UV : This property shows the UV color.

Normal Painting is a type of map source that enhances surface detail by applying height and normal information to give a sense of depth to the mesh surface.

In the Map Source group properties, click Add Map Source > Height. A Height Map Source will be added. Check Height as Normal. Change the Material Mode to Preview to see the Height-Normal applied in real-time.

Determines the height value of the Brush. Based on a Background Value of 0.5, values closer to 0 will appear as engraving, while values closer to 1 will appear as embossing.

Adjusts the intensity of slopes when generating a normal map from height map information.

The Layer group in Painting Mode is the group in which layers are displayed, along with tools to manage and edit them. info The Layers.​ A Layer is an organization of layers of images that can be edited individually. The layers overlap from top to bottom, and the effect of each layer is calculated by a formula called a blending mode, which ultimately results in a single image.

To run the Painting 2D Editor, follow the steps below.
Select the Source Mesh. Press the Editor button at the top right of the mode. Launch the Painting2D Tool from the menu. You can see the Painting2D Editor.
Select the UModelerX object. Click the Painting 2D Editor tab among the open tabs to activate it. note If the UModeler X Object is not selected, the Painting 2D Editor will not be activated.

The Preference Window is where you can configure various options to make some of the functionality of UModeler X easily accessible and usable.
It can be accessed by navigating to Edit > Preferences > UModeler X in the Unity Editor.

Auto Unwrap Shape : Sets the shape for auto unwrapping Auto Generate Mesh Collider : Automatically generates a mesh collider UModelerize Merge Vertices : Merges vertices during UModelerize Create As Static Object : Creates the object as a static object Static Option : Sets the static options Always Enable Grid Snap : Always enables grid snapping Create Under Root : Creates under the root object White Box Mode : Sets the white box mode Save data in the scene folder(Scene Save Asset) : The data of newly created UModelerX objects is specified by the Save data in the scene folder option in the Local Setting Tool.
