When manipulating the movement, rotation, and size of a UV element, the position of the element is snapped according to the SnapType property and other properties related to snapping. info Snap​ Snapping is a feature for placing an element in a precise location. Using a number of properties and predefined values, you can edit elements in a precise and efficient manner, such as moving them to a specific location or rotating them by a specific angle. None World Increment Pixel Properties Tab SnapType: None​ Properties when no snapping is applied. Properties Tab SnapType: World​ Property by which UV vertices are snapped to the grid in the UV Editor workspace. GridSnapSize Property​ Property that sets the spacing of the grid that UV vertices are snapped to when the UV element is moved, rotated, or scaled. Properties Tab SnapType: Increment​ A property that causes the selected UV element to be moved and rotated without snapping the UV vertices by the value set in the SnapSize property. GridSnapSize Property​ Property that sets the snap size to be applied when moving UV elements. RotationSnapSize Property​ Property that sets the snap angle to be applied when rotating the UV element. Properties Tab SnapType: Pixel​ This property causes UV vertices to snap to the pixels of the applied texture. PixelCenter​ This property causes the vertices to snap to the center of the pixels in the texture. If disabled, it will snap to the pixel edge of the texture. tip The Pixel property is primarily useful when creating pixel art style models. caution When using the Pixel property, the snapping interval follows the resolution of the texture representing the pixel art, so the represented pixel size should not be different from the actual resolution of the texture.

Snapping is a feature for placing an element in a precise location. Using a number of properties and predefined values, you can edit elements in a precise and efficient manner, such as moving them to a specific location or rotating them by a specific angle.
Properties when no snapping is applied.

Property by which UV vertices are snapped to the grid in the UV Editor workspace. GridSnapSize Property​ Property that sets the spacing of the grid that UV vertices are snapped to when the UV element is moved, rotated, or scaled.

A property that causes the selected UV element to be moved and rotated without snapping the UV vertices by the value set in the SnapSize property. GridSnapSize Property​ Property that sets the snap size to be applied when moving UV elements. RotationSnapSize Property​ Property that sets the snap angle to be applied when rotating the UV element.

This property causes UV vertices to snap to the pixels of the applied texture. PixelCenter​ This property causes the vertices to snap to the center of the pixels in the texture. If disabled, it will snap to the pixel edge of the texture. tip The Pixel property is primarily useful when creating pixel art style models. caution When using the Pixel property, the snapping interval follows the resolution of the texture representing the pixel art, so the represented pixel size should not be different from the actual resolution of the texture.
Property to show the bounding box of the UV island.
Property that makes the UV faces translucent. tip By making the UV faces translucent, you can easily see the overlapping UV faces by their translucent concentration difference.
Property that displays a grid in the UV Editor workspace.

Property that shows the U and V axes corresponding to the X and Y axes in the UV Editor workspace. note The texture space​ The texture space is from the start point of the UV axis to the point where a widely spaced Fixed Grid Line coincides with the UV axis. Unless you are representing a texture that is largely tiled, all UV elements should be placed within the texture space.

The texture space is from the start point of the UV axis to the point where a widely spaced Fixed Grid Line coincides with the UV axis. Unless you are representing a texture that is largely tiled, all UV elements should be placed within the texture space.
Property that displays the material's texture, as set in the UV Editor's Material property.
This property displays the material's texture alpha channel, excluding the portion set in the UV Editor's Material properties.
Property to display the material's texture as a left-right repeat, as set in the UV Editor's Material properties.
Property that displays the material's texture, as set in the UV Editor's Material property, as an up and down repeat.

A property that shows the materials applied with the Material tool, displaying only the UV elements that have that material assigned to them. All​ A property that shows all UV elements regardless of material assignment.
The area where you edit UV elements, allowing you to see the texture along with the grid.
This is a collection of tools for editing UV elements, such as expanding, selecting, and placing UV elements.
This group contains tools for unwrapping UV elements. 📄️ Unwrap Group
This group contains tools for selecting UV elements. 📄️ Selection Group
This group contains tools that allow you to easily flip and rotate the position of UV elements. 📄️ Quick Transform Group
This group contains tools for aligning the position of UV elements. 📄️ Alignment Group
This group contains tools used to break and weld UV elements together. 📄️ Weld And Break Group
This group contains tools for placing UV elements in texture space in bulk. 📄️ Arrange Group
This group contains tools that do not belong in any other group. 📄️ Misc Group
The Space H tool in the UV Editor is a tool that will horizontally align selected UV vertices to be equally spaced.
Select the UV vertices. Run the Space H Tool. Selected UV vertices are horizontally aligned with equal spacing.

The Shared tool in the UV Editor selects UV elements that are shared with the selected UV. note For a Shared Element​ A shared element is an element that is separated by a UV, but is attached or adjacent to it in the mesh. UV Color Shared elements are colored blue (default).
A shared element is an element that is separated by a UV, but is attached or adjacent to it in the mesh. UV Color Shared elements are colored blue (default).
Select a vertex. Run the Shared tool. A vertex that shares a mesh with the selected vertex is selected.
Select an edge. Run the Shared tool. Edges that share a mesh with the selected edge are selected.
The Space V Tool in the UV Editor is a tool that will vertically align selected UV vertices to be equally spaced.
Select the UV vertices. Run the Space V Tool. Selected UV vertices are vertically aligned with equal spacing.
The Top Tool in the UV Editor is a tool that aligns selected UV elements upward.
Select the UV elements. Run the Top Tool. The selected UV elements will be aligned upwards.
The Weld To Center Tool in the UV Editor merges vertices to the center of selected UV vertices.
Select the UV vertices to be connected. Run the Weld To Center Tool. The vertices will be welded to the center of the selected vertices.
The Weld To First Tool in the UV Editor merges selected UV vertices to the location of the first selected vertex.
Select the UV vertices to be connected. Run the Weld To First Tool. The selected vertices will be welded to the position of the first selected vertex.
The Weld To Last Tool in the UV Editor merges selected UV vertices to the location of the last selected vertex.
Select the UV vertices to be connected. Run the Weld To Last Tool. The selected vertices will be welded to the position of the last selected vertex.

Vertices are the points that make up a mesh, and moving or editing a vertex affects the elements associated with it. You can view properties related to Vertices by pressing the keyboard shortcut Shift+1, or by using the buttons at the top of the scene. note Shortcut Shift+Click Drag​ When you select a vertex and move it using Shift held down with click drag, the selected vertex is duplicated. An edge is automatically created between the selected vertex and the newly created vertex.

When you select a vertex and move it using Shift held down with click drag, the selected vertex is duplicated. An edge is automatically created between the selected vertex and the newly created vertex.
These are the properties that are displayed for the Element group when a vertex is selected.
Properties that allow you to choose how the mesh is displayed.
Allows you to show or hide vertices.
Properties that allow you to set how vertices are selected.

Allows you to set whether vertices facing the opposite direction are selected. When the Backface Select property is off, opposite facing vertices are not selected. When the Backface Select property is on, opposite facing vertices are selected as well.

This property selects only the currently visible vertices based on the camera. When the Camera Based Select property is off, vertices that are obscured by the camera are also selected. When the Camera Based Select property is on, vertices that are hidden by the camera are not selected.

This property selects vertices in the Scene that are adjacent to the selected vertex on a weighted basis. The vertices selected by weight and the range you set are displayed in color, usually as a soft circle.
A graph-like property that determines the shape of the Soft Selection. Tap the graph next to the Soft Selection Curve property to edit it.
Examples of how the selection shape changes depending on the Curve shape. Example 1 Example 2
This property sets the range from the selected vertex to which the soft selection is applied. In Unity, 1m = 1.0, so a value of 0.5 will select up to 50cm from the selected vertex.
A Property that is displayed when an element is moved indicates the distance traveled.

Say goodbye to juggling multiple software tools for modeling, rigging, and texturing UModeler X is here to revolutionize your workflow. Seamlessly integrated within Unity, UModeler X allows you to handle all these tasks directly inside the engine, making your development process more efficient and streamlined. Why Choose UModeler X? Ease of Use: With UModeler X, you only need to master Unity to create stunning 3D models, intricate rigs, and detailed textures. No need to purchase or learn additional software—everything you need is right at your fingertips. Cost-Effective: UModeler X is completely free, providing you with a powerful suite of tools without the hefty price tag. This means more budget for other aspects of your project and fewer hurdles to start creating. Seamless Integration: Since UModeler X operates entirely within Unity, your workflow remains uninterrupted. This tight integration ensures that your assets are always compatible and your project stays on track. Perfect for ZEPETO Item Creation: Whether you're an indie developer or part of a larger team, UModeler X simplifies the process of creating items for ZEPETO. Design, rig, and texture your items with ease, and see your creations come to life in the ZEPETO world. With UModeler X, transforming your ideas into reality has never been easier. Dive into Unity, explore the robust features of UModeler X, and start creating amazing 3D content today. Experience the future of modeling with UModeler X—your free, all-in-one solution within Unity.

documents.t: Getting Started with UModeler X introduces the necessary software and guides you through the installation process to get you up and running. Getting Started Check
Exploring the Interface explains the interfaces of both Unity and UModeler X, helping you navigate and utilize the tools effectively. Exploring Interface Check

Basics of Modeling is designed for beginners, breaking down the elements of 3D modeling and providing a comprehensive guide to the essential functions needed to create models. Basics of modeling Check
Modeling Applications offers important tips and guidelines for creating ZEPETO items using UModeler X, ensuring your models meet the necessary standards and requirements. Modeling Applications Check
UV and Texturing provides a detailed guide on how to handle UV mapping and texturing within UModeler X, allowing you to add intricate details and finishes to your models. UV and Texturing Check
Rigging covers the process of rigging in UModeler X, showing you how to create and manipulate bones and joints to bring your models to life. Rigging Check

Uploading guides you through the process of uploading your finished items to the ZEPETO Studio, ensuring your creations are ready for use in the ZEPETO platform. Uploading Check

3D objects consist of elements called vertices, edges, and faces. When two vertices are connected, they form an edge, and when at least three edges converge, they form a face. Faces with three points are called Triangle, with four points are called quad, and with more points are called N-gons or polygons. When multiple faces are connected, they form a single object. 3D modeling involves adding or moving these vertices, edges, and faces to create shapes. danger While 3D software interprets objects' faces as triangles for recognition, it's much more convenient for modeling to use quad shapes rather than triangles. Thus, it's recommended to model in quad shapes whenever possible. Also, be cautious with N-gons, as they can cause issues during subdivision, UV mapping, or rigging. In UModeler X, you can modify these three elements and select each one using the icons provided. When you select an element, it's highlighted in the Scene View, and options specific to that element appear in the inspector window.
The Multiple Object group provides options like Combine, Pivot, and Reset X Form for multiple selected objects.
Combine merges selected objects into one.
Pivot sets the pivot point for multiple objects simultaneously.
Reset X Form resets transform values for multiple objects.

Boolean performs Boolean operations on multiple objects, such as union, intersection, or difference. It's commonly used for creating symmetrical objects or subtracting one object from another. Multiple Objects Group For more detailed information, please check the following link Check
For more detailed information, please check the following link Check

The Add group is a collection of tools that, when executed, will add each element (Vertex, Edge, Face). It usually contains tools that either add selected elements or add elements defined in the tool.
Select an element and choose Duplicate to create a copy of it.
Select an element and press Bevel to round its edges
Connect creates an edge between two selected vertices or edges.
Bridge connects two elements together, filling gaps or connecting separate edges.
Subdivide divides faces, either partially or for the entire object. Be cautious with excessive subdivision, as it can affect performance and modeling convenience.
Loopcut adds additional edges along the modeling surface for more details.

Slice cut creates edges based on a line drawn on the object's surface. You can move or rotate the virtual plane directly, or click both endpoints to draw a virtual line segment to create a virtual plane. Split Only: Cuts the mesh based on the virtual plane. Remove Above: Deletes the parts below the virtual plane. Remove Below: Deletes the parts above the virtual plane.
Insert adds faces inside the selected face.
Insert vertex allows you to add a vertex on an edge as desired. Add Group For more detailed information, please check the following link Check
For more detailed information, please check the following link Check
You can create 3D shapes with Primitive Shapes
You can create 2D shapes with Drawing. Primitive Shapes Group For more detailed information, please check the following link Check
For more detailed information, please check the following link Check

The Deform group includes brush-like tools for surface manipulation, rather than editing at the element level. Brush tools allow you to adjust the brush size by moving the mouse up or down while holding the Shift key or using shortcuts like [,].
The Relax Brush evens out vertex spacing while maintaining the shape.
The Smooth Brush softens shapes while maintaining vertex spacing.
The Standard Brush pushes surfaces outward. Pressing the Ctrl key while brushing will cause the surface to go inward.
The Pinch Brush brings vertices closer together, creating sharper edges. Deform Group For more detailed information, please check the following link Check
For more detailed information, please check the following link Check
The Misc group contains miscellaneous tools.
Reset X Form resets an object's transform values.
Flip flips the normal direction of selected faces, affecting how they're displayed.
Pivot changes the pivot point position of objects. Misc Group For more detailed information, please check the following link Check
For more detailed information, please check the following link Check

Modifiers provide a non-destructive way to modify the original model. You can accumulate edits using the modifier stack or toggle specific modifiers on and off for editing. You can add modifiers with the + icon, delete them with the - icon, or merge them with the Source Mesh. Be cautious when merging, as it may make modifying the original mesh difficult. You can rearrange modifiers, rename them, or toggle their activation freely.
The Bend modifier bends objects along a specified axis and angle.
The Subdivide modifier smooths surfaces by subdividing faces. You can adjust the level of subdivision.
The Shell modifier adds thickness to objects based on the source mesh.
The Mirror modifier creates a mirrored object based on a specified axis.
The FFD modifier provides a grid-based box for manipulating meshes. The vertices of the grid move along with nearby vertices of the source mesh.
The Push modifier moves faces along or against their normals.

The Decimate modifier reduces the polygon count of models. Be mindful of how it may alter the model's shape based on options. Modifier For more detailed information, please check the following link Check
For more detailed information, please check the following link Check

The Remove group is a collection of tools that, when executed, will remove each element (Vertex, Edge, Face). It mainly contains tools that either remove selected elements or merge elements by the tool.

Detach separates selected faces or elements, either within the same object or as a new object. Holding the Alt key and clicking Detach allows you to choose the Type. In "To Element" mode, Detach will separate the face, but it will remain within the same object. In "To Object" mode, Detach will create a new object in the Hierarchy, and you will see that the selected face has been separated into this new object.
Eraser deletes selected elements. You can also use the delete key for quick deletion.
Target Weld connects selected vertices to each other.
Collapse merges selected elements into one. Note that this works only for connected groups.
Merge combines selected vertices into one. Depending on the options, the merge can occur at different points between the selected vertices.
Weld joins vertices within a specified distance of each other.
Combine Face merges selected faces into one. Note that this may not work well with heavily curved or N-gon shapes. Remove Group For more detailed information, please check the following link Check
For more detailed information, please check the following link Check
Exploring the Interface explains the interfaces of both Unity and UModeler X, helping you navigate and utilize the tools effectively.
To select an element, click on the desired element in the Scene View. You can select multiple elements by dragging over them.
You can deselect them by clicking in an empty space on the screen.
You can also hold down the Shift key to add more elements to the selection or hold down the Ctrl key while clicking to deselect elements.
This feature allows you to select faces that are not visible from the current viewpoint.
This mode restricts the selection to only the faces, edges, or vertices that are visible from the current camera view.
The Border tool enables you to select and manipulate the edges that define the boundary of a selected area.
Soft Select allows for a gradient-based selection, affecting not only the selected element but also those around it with a falloff effect.
The All tool is a tool that selects all selected elements.
The Invert tool selects the inverted portion of the selected element.
The Isolate tool is a tool that selects the selected element and its connected parts together.
The Grow tool expands the area of the selected element and is selected. If no element is selected, or if there is no more area to expand, it will not work.
The Shrink tool is a tool that shrinks an area on selected elements. It does not work if there is no element selected
The Loop tool is a tool that allows you to select by concatenating the selected element with elements in the aligned direction.
The Ring tool is a tool that selects elements parallel to the selected element.
The Border Tool is a tool that selects all the edges of an object. Selection Group For more detailed information, please check the following link Check
For more detailed information, please check the following link Check

You can import modeling or texture files from external sources by dragging and dropping them into the desired folder in the Project panel. To view the imported models, drag and drop them into the Hierarchy. External models cannot be edited directly. To modify these models with UModeler X, right-click on the object and select UModeler X - UModelerize.

In Unity, you typically import modeling files from external sources and use them in the scene. As a result, models created with UModeler X cannot exist solely within the scene. When you save a scene file that includes models created with UModeler X, the UModeler X files and modeling files are automatically saved in the folder where the scene file is located, using the scene name. For easier management, it is convenient to create separate folders for each item and name the scenes after the items.

You can set UModeler X shortcuts using the Unity Shortcut Manager, accessible through the Edit > Shortcuts menu in Unity's top menu. In Unity, the default profile has shortcuts registered for general use, but when a UModeler X object is selected, a separate shortcut profile is utilized. Upon installing UModeler X in a project, two profiles are created: UMX-EdMesh-Edit : Shortcut profile for Edit Mode. UMX-EdMesh-Obj : Shortcut profile for Object Mode.
For more detailed information, please check the following link Check
Clicking the middle mouse button while moving the mouse allows you to move the screen.
Using the mouse wheel or holding the Alt key and clicking the right mouse button while moving allows you to zoom in or out.
Holding the Alt key and clicking the left button while moving the mouse allows you to rotate the screen.
You can also move to fixed views like Front, Side, or Top View using the Orientation overlay in the Scene View, and you can also fix them if necessary.

Moving is done by pressing Move on the Toolbar or pressing the W key on the keyboard, which reveals the Move Gizmo. You can move along a single axis by dragging an arrow or move along two axes by clicking the center square.
Rotation is done by pressing Rotate on the Toolbar or pressing the E key on the keyboard, revealing the Rotate Gizmo. You can rotate by dragging the circle around the GameObject.

Scaling is done by pressing Scale on the Toolbar or pressing the R key on the keyboard, revealing the Scale Gizmo. You can scale in one direction or proportionally along three axes using the center cube.

Center, rotating or resizing a GameObject will be based on the center of the GameObject's shape. Pivot rotating or resizing will be based on the position of the Gizmo, allowing you to rotate or resize around the position of the Gizmo.

Global always shows the Gizmo based on the global axis, regardless of how the GameObject is rotated or transformed. Switching to Local shows the Gizmo of the GameObject based on its rotated direction.
Grid Snap option allows you to move in increments of the size of the grid at the bottom while moving. You can adjust the grid in the Scene View's icon for axis and size changes.
You can adjust an object's position, rotation, and scale by changing the transform values in the Inspector.
UModeler X has three main modes: Modeling mode, Rigging mode, and Painting mode. When initially opened from the Inspector panel, it defaults to Modeling Mode.

Modeling mode, you perform tasks such as creating and modifying shapes. After selecting a Primitive shape or Drawing, you drag to create the base and then move the mouse to set the height of the object. Objects created like this can be modified by changing the values in the Tool Properties. Basics of modeling Check

Painting mode allows you to add colors to objects with UVs created like this. You can add layers to draw desired colors or load textures. You can use brushes in the Scene view to paint or use paint 2D to draw on a 2D plane. Painting Check

Rigging mode involves rigging bones to characters or objects and assigning them so that the object moves according to the bone's movement. You can create bones or assign modeling to bones using tools. Rigging Check
UV refers to the 2D layout of a 3D object's surface, which is used to apply colors or materials. The UV editor is where you can create and modify these UV maps. UV Editor Check
The Painting 2D window allows you to paint in 2D mode instead of the 3D view when you are in painting mode.
Here’s a breakdown of the key components of the Unity interface:

The Hierarchy panel on the right lists all GameObjects within the scene in a hierarchical manner. When creating objects using UModeler X or by clicking the + icon in the Hierarchy panel to generate GameObjects such as Modeling, Lighting, or Camera, they will appear in this panel.
The Scene view allows you to view GameObjects in 3D or 2D perspective, enabling you to inspect their shapes, positions, etc. (indicated by camera, light, and modeling icons).

The GameView displays how the final rendered game will appear. You can preview it by pressing the play button, showing the view from cameras placed within the scene. info Currently in Zepeto Studio, you can enter a scene set up for inspecting items and see how they appear when various body shapes are applied, and animations are applied.

The Inspector panel displays the properties of selected GameObjects within the scene. For example, when selecting a Cylinder, properties related to its position, rotation, size, mesh type, rendering method, collider options, and material-related menus will appear. When selecting a GameObject created with UModeler X, menu options related to UModeler X will appear under Transform, allowing you to modify the modeling.

The Project panel displays all Asset Libraries available for use in Zepeto Studio. The left side shows the actual project folder structure, while the right side displays assets within folders. Any assets created using other tools and imported into the project will be displayed here.
UModeler X is represented by an icon in the Scene view.

Clicking the logo icon reveals information such as UModeler X version management and logged-in account details. You can check the version of UModeler X and update it in the All Products section. In the Assets section, you can download the assets needed for creating ZEPETO items.
This is the icon used to create or modify a UModeler X GameObject. Clicking the icon opens the UModeler X menu in the Inspector.
You can select UI options when using UModeler X. You can change the color and thickness when displaying vertices, edges, faces, etc.
Before uploading an item, you need to perform masking on the avatar. Masking is the process of covering the parts of the avatar that will be hidden by the ZEPETO item you created.

The object used for masking can be obtained from UModeler X. You can find the imported object at the following path. Bring the mask object into the scene and move it under the item as follows. Select the mask object, right-click on it, and select Prefab - Unpack to make it editable.

In ZEPETO, masking work uses vertex colors. You can modify vertex colors in modeling mode using the surface's vertex color or the vertex color brush. Vertex Color Brush: This tool allows you to change the color of vertices using a brush. Vertex Color: This feature lets you change the color of the selected vertices. By using these tools, you can adjust the vertex colors to achieve the desired masking effect. For more detailed instructions, please refer to the card below. Vertex Color Brush Check Vertex Color Check

Use this feature to paint the areas hidden by the created item in black. Turn on the visibility of the item to check if the black areas are visible. If any black masks are visible outside the areas covered by the item, change them to white.

To create ZEPETO items, you need to open the ZEPETO Studio Unity file. When using UModelerX for modeling in Unity, it's challenging to use the guide modeling provided by ZEPETO Studio. Therefore, UModelerX offers separate assets for ZEPETO Studio item creation. Click on the UModelerX icon and import the Rigging Help Meshes For Zepeto file from the Assets. Confirm that it has been imported correctly.

The directory structure can be created arbitrarily, but let's create a folder with the name of the item to be created inside the Contents folder. When you right-click on the Contents folder and select Folder under Create, a new folder will be created under the Contents folder. his will create a new folder under the Contents folder. Rename it to the item's name. If you accidentally clicked on something else and couldn't rename it, right-click on the created folder, select rename, and change the name. Go into the created folder, right-click on empty space, select Create, then Scene to create a new scene. The UModelerX modeling file to be created in this scene will be automatically generated in the folder where this scene is saved, so choose the name carefully. Double-click to open this scene.

Now, let's bring in the guide files for the item we are creating. When doing modeling work, you can use the Mask prefab inside the ZepetoRiggingHelperMeshes folder. Drag the Mask prefab into the Scene View. The prefabs brought in as guides should always be loaded with position, rotation and scale values set to 0. When dragged into the Scene view, numerical values may be assigned, but when dragged into the Hierarchy, they will be loaded with values of 0.

If the Scene view has lighting turned on, you may notice that the modeling appears to be backlit. If this is inconvenient, you can select the Directional Light and rotate it using the rotate tool or the shortcut key E to adjust the direction of the light before working. Alternatively, you can also turn off the light and work under flat lighting conditions, which can be more convenient.

Modeling involves not only the shape of the outline but also the connectivity of each vertex, which forms the faces. This arrangement of faces is referred to as mesh topology. Mesh topology is crucial not only for the convenience of modeling but also for rigging tasks that will be carried out later. The conditions for good topology are as follows: faces should be appropriately distributed and arranged according to the object's shape. Moreover, edges should form loops, and it's advisable to avoid too many polygons clustered around a single vertex. Additionally, there are other aspects of topology work that need to be addressed for rigging purposes. Typically, areas where the mesh bends, such as joints in clothing like tops or bottoms, require additional edges. These areas, known as joint bands, need additional edges around the joint to prevent angular deformation when bent. Adding extra edges in these areas helps to smooth out the modeling when bent.

For clothing items, it's easier to approach the modeling by referencing the wires of the character in the ZEPETO item guide file. Aligning the major flow of the wires and adding additional edges where there are joint bands ensures smooth functioning during rigging.

When creating objects like skirts, if there aren't enough vertical lines, errors may occur when the legs pass through the skirt. Clothing items should be designed with enough detail to accommodate character movement.

When modeling with only cross-sections rather than solid shapes, faces may appear or disappear depending on the direction of the face. When modeling with only cross-sections, it's important to keep in mind that the back faces are not visible. If you notice any incorrectly displayed normals, you can use the Flip function in the modeling tool to reverse them.

ZEPETO items have a limit on the maximum number of polygons. If you create an item with too many polygons, it might get rejected during the review process. Each ZEPETO item must be modeled with a number of triangles below a certain limit. You can check the number of triangles in the modeling by selecting the corresponding part in the prefab generated when saving the scene file in Unity. You can find the number of triangles for the modeling at the bottom right when you select the relevant part in the generated prefab. If you want to check your modeling in real-time, you can turn on EdMesh Info in the settings of UModelerX and select the object to see it. Please check the maximum number of triangles for each item at the following link. At the bottom of the Item_guidelines page, check "Sort items by category" and ensure your work adheres to the specified standards.

Sometimes, the surface of the model may appear faceted. In such cases, select all the faces you want to change and assign them the same smoothing group number. You will then see that the surface of the model has become smoother.

It's recommended to position the pivot at the center or at coordinates 0,0,0. Also, ensure that the position and rotation values of Transform are set to 0. If not, use Reset XForm the values. I've looked into what you need to know when modeling for ZEPETO item creation. Next time, we'll explore how to create UVs and textures for modeling.

After completing the modeling and texture work, import the WeightTransferMesh_APose prefab into the scene containing the finished model. Confirm that both the position and rotation values of the created item and the WeightTransferMesh_APose prefab's transform are all set to 0. In the hierarchy, right-click on the WeightTransferMesh_APose prefab and select Unpack Prefab to unpack it. Then, rearrange the hierarchy structure as follows: choose a name for the item, and underneath it, paste the hips from the unpacked WeightTransferMesh_APose using Ctrl+C and Ctrl+V. Alternatively, you can use the COPY and PASTE commands. Let's hide the A POSE object and start rigging the hirts object.

Select the item object, then in the Rigging tab, drag and drop hips onto the root bone. Then, click on Start Rigging. Since the hips group cannot proceed with rigging directly using the existing bone data imported into Unity, this step is necessary to make UModeler X recognize it and place it into the Bone Tree. Once rigging begins, a "Skinned Mesh Renderer" tab will appear below in the Inspector, indicating that the object has been rigged. tip Sometimes the vertices appear too large and can interfere with your work. In such cases, you can adjust the vertex size in the settings to make them more manageable.

You can easily identify the position of bones by selecting their names in the Bone Tree and moving them in the Scene view. Alternatively, you can enable the Enable Clicking on Bone option in the Tool Properties. With this enabled, you can directly select bones in the Scene view while holding down the Shift key.
Weights allow you to see the influence each selected vertex has from each bone, and you can easily adjust the weight of specific bones.

Select a vertex and then choose the desired bone. Adjust the value by selecting a number or sliding the slider, then press "Apply Weight" to assign the weight value. you can adjust the slider at the bottom to directly modify the weight value of the bone already connected.

You can also use the weight brush to paint and adjust weight values. Select the bone you want to adjust and paint with the brush. If the weight brush type is set to Add, the values will increase; if set to Subtract, the values will decrease. You can use Blur to smooth the values between vertices, making transitions more natural.

During this process, the bone positions may change significantly from the original pose. Since rigging should always be done with the original pose in mind, after the work is done, use the "Reset Poses" tool to reset the poses to their initial state.

The "Rebind Poses" tool is used when you want to change the bone positions during rigging. After moving the bones, clicking "Rebind Poses" will move the vertices affected by the bone movement back to their original positions. danger However, it's important to note that you should never change the positions of the bones imported from the A Pose. Please only use this tool when you need to work with swing bones later on.
"Weight transfer" is a feature that copies weight values from an existing mesh. Simply select the reference mesh and press "Transfer".

Weight Mirror is a feature that copies weight values from one side to the other. When you have an object with different weights on each side, pressing Mirror will apply the same values to the opposite side.
The Auto Weight tool automatically assigns weights to vertices based on their proximity to bones. Adjust the weight width to set the range and then press "Apply Auto Weight".

Enveloping is a method of assigning weight values based on the size and position of an envelope capsule. Select the desired bone, adjust the position and size of the envelope capsule, then apply the envelope. This applies the skinning values accordingly.
The Edit Bones Tool is a tool that allows you to edit bones, including adding, deleting, separating, etc.

Now, let's rig the actual ZEPETO item. To streamline the process, use auto weight to perform the initial rigging. Move the bones and check for any issues around the joints. If there are any indentations or deformations at the joints, use the weight brush to correct them. Select the bone you want to adjust and use the brush to modify the weight values, making the joint bends look natural. Once you have finished adjusting, click reset poses to reset the bone positions. Continue checking the other joints to ensure there are no issues. After finishing one arm, use mirror weight to copy the weights to the other arm, ensuring both sides are identical.

In addition, there are cases where additional bones need to be added for secondary movement such as earrings, hair, or tails, which are not present in the existing animations. This is called the swing bone operation. To perform swing bone operations, you need to add new bones. Press "Edit Bones", select the closest bone to where you want to create the new bone, then enter the name and press "Add" to create the bone. You don't need to add too many bones, just enough to avoid looking too stiff. After adding the bones, proceed with the skinning operation. The swing bone moves in accordance with the existing animation. This movement is based on the physics_drag_angle drag_restore drag values. drag determines how much the bone moves. Lower values result in more movement, while higher values make it stiffer. The optimal range is typically between 7 to 17. angle drag controls the rotation angle of the joint. Lower values result in larger swings, while higher values produce smaller swings. The suitable range is generally between 10 to 25. restore drag determines the strength of returning to the initial position. Lower values lead to slower returns, giving a water-like feeling, whereas higher values result in faster returns. The recommended range is typically between 15 to 30. You can assign these values only to the topmost swing bone, or if you want different values for each swing bone, you can append physics_drag_angle drag_restore drag after each swing bone name. After rigging is completed, press Reset Pose to reset the pose to its initial state. Rigging Mode For more detailed information, please check the following link Check

Click on Export. Ensure that .prefab for ZEPETO is selected, then Export again, name the file, and save it in the working folder.

Open the playground scene in the Assets. Select the LOADER and choose the category for the item you created. Since we made a shirt, check ClothesTop. Connect the previously saved item prefab to this. Press the play button to check if the item appears correctly. Change the body shape and apply animations to ensure there are no issues.

Right-click on the created prefab and select ZEPETO Studio - Export as .zepeto. After a short while, the ZEPETO file will be generated. Right-click on the generated file and select Show in Explorer to open the folder containing the file.

Log in to the ZEPETO Studio website and go to Manage Contents. ZEPETO Studio website Click on +Create and select Items. Choose Create as 3D file and select the category for the item you created. Drag and drop the ZEPETO file you just created to upload it. If the texture size is too large or there are other issues, an error message will appear. If there are no issues, proceed to the next screen as shown. In the Detail section, fill in the required information and set the price. Refer to the guide to complete the empty fields. Once all fields are completed, click Submit for Review to finish the upload process. Within a few days, you will receive a message via the ZEPETO app indicating whether your submission has been approved or rejected. If rejected, refer to the guide, make the necessary corrections, and upload it again. By following the guidelines in the link below, you can easily create items that meet the required standards. In the Preparing_modeling section, you can check the item categories. In the Contents_guidelines section, you can find the content standards related to copyright and harmful content. In the Item_guidelines section, you can check the specifications for thumbnails, resources, and the maximum polygon count for each item category.
UV mapping is a crucial process in 3D modeling and texturing, allowing you to project a 2D image texture onto a 3D model. Here's an overview of what UV mapping entails:
U and V represent the axes of the 2D texture map. Unlike the X, Y, and Z coordinates in 3D space, U and V are used to denote the horizontal and vertical axes of the texture, respectively.

UV mapping is used to accurately apply textures (images) to the surface of 3D models. It defines how a 2D texture is wrapped around a 3D object, ensuring that the texture aligns correctly with the model's geometry.

Unwrapping: The first step in UV mapping is unwrapping the 3D model. This involves creating a 2D representation (UV map) of the 3D model’s surface. Think of it like peeling an orange and laying the peel flat. Laying Out UVs: The unwrapped 2D pieces are then laid out in the UV space, ensuring that they fit within the 0 to 1 range on both the U and V axes. This layout determines how the texture will be applied to the model. Assigning Textures: After the UVs are laid out, you can assign a 2D texture to the model. The texture is then projected onto the 3D model according to the UV map.

Texture Accuracy: Proper UV mapping ensures that textures are applied accurately, without distortion, stretching, or seams. Detail Control: UV mapping allows for precise control over where and how textures are placed on a model, enabling detailed and complex texturing work. Optimization: Efficient UV mapping can optimize texture usage, reducing the amount of texture space needed and improving performance.

UV mapping is used in various fields such as video game development, film production, and 3D printing. It is essential for creating realistic textures, materials, and visual effects. By understanding and mastering UV mapping, you can significantly enhance the visual quality and realism of your 3D models, ensuring that textures are applied smoothly and accurately. Let's work with the UV image exported from Photoshop. First, invert the imported UV by pressing Control + I. Set the blending mode to Multiply. Lock this layer to prevent any modifications. Create a new layer and apply the desired color. If you want to add a logo, estimate its position based on the UV lines and place it accordingly, such as on the front upper part. Hide the UV lines by turning off the visibility of the layer and save the file in the desired location. You can then import this texture into Unity for use.

Entering Painting 3D shows the painting environment. Specify the texture resolution, select Materials as Zepeto, and click START PAINTING to begin painting. When working in 3D, layers aren't limited to handling colors only; they also allow for adjusting materials.

In MAP SOURCE, you can press '+' to create layers for manipulating attributes like metallicness, highlights, height, or emissive materials. Attributes of these created layers can be adjusted within the layer settings. info ZEPETO has strict limitations on texture sizes, and having too many maps can lead to rejection during the review process. Therefore, it is recommended to keep the texture size to a maximum of 1024 and primarily work with ALBEDO maps for color changes.

You can add various layers by pressing + such as the PAINT LAYER for drawing with brushes, the FILL LAYER for filling the entire area, or the STICKER LAYER for partially applying specific images. You have the flexibility to toggle visibility for specific layers and rearrange their stacking order via drag and drop. Depending on the blending mode, layers can appear as they are, be multiplied or added, and you can adjust opacity to control the concentration. You can also create groups to manage layers or control the visibility of groups. Additionally, you can use the solo feature to view only the selected layer. Each layer also allows you to add masks to adjust the visible portions. By selecting 'albedo,' you can choose different map sources to handle other maps for materials, allowing you to modify them accordingly.

It fills with a single color or texture. You can change the color in COLOR or drag and drop an image onto TEXTURE to fill with an image. The Tilling option allows for repetition and offsetting of the image.

The sticker layer allows you to attach specific images to certain areas. By pressing [ , ] or the ctrl key and moving the mouse in the scene view, you can change the size and rotation of the projected plane. When clicking on an object, you can see the image projected from that direction.

The paint layer allows you to paint using brushes. You can switch between the scene view and the painting 2D window to paint. You can adjust brush options and use the eraser tool to erase. You can also paint polygon by polygon or area by area. In the painting layer, you can also use AI features. Please refer to the help manual for the installation method of stable diffusion. Select the shader, then choose ZEPETO > Built-in > Cloth. This will give you a shader that more closely resembles clothing material. UVs should generally be laid out so that they do not overlap unless they use the same texture. For clothing, it is best to arrange the UVs to resemble the pattern of actual garments as closely as possible. Use Mark UV Seam to indicate the fabric seams and LSCM to simplify the process. Additionally, create a basic material using a checker map and apply it to the model. If the checker map's squares are uniform and evenly distributed, the UVs are properly laid out.
UV mapping corresponds to a 2D unfolded map. For 3D objects, textures and colors can be applied using 2D coordinates called UVs. You can perform this task by navigating to Editor -> UVEditor.

The UV editor interface is quite similar to the scene view and shares similar shortcuts. You can navigate the screen using the icons at the top or by using the spacebar, and you can move, rotate, and scale using the W, E, R keys, respectively. You can also use the rectangle tool to adjust the position and size using rectangular corners. The icons on the side represent uv vertex, uv edge, uv face, and the last icon is for selecting connected uv elements. The gear icon is for settings. Here, you can modify settings like snap and other UV editor configurations. The central window displays the UV values of the selected object. You can arrange the UVs in this window to work on textures.
Unwrap projects the 3D object onto a 2D plane. Select the faces of the 3D object and execute the necessary unwrap.
Plane is used for planar projection. You can project along each axis, toward the world axis direction, or toward the average normal direction of the faces.
Cube unfolds UVs based on the direction the selected face is facing (x, y, z).
Auto layout automatically unfolds selected faces.

LSCM cuts UV edges arbitrarily using the MARK UV Sceam and UNMARK UV Sceam tools in the modeling tool to unfold UVs along those cut edges. Select the desired edge and click MARK UV Seam to create an orange line, indicating the UV seam. To remove the seam, select the edge again and click UNMARK UV Seam. Using this method, select the face where you want the seams and then click LSCM. The UV will unfold based on these marked seams.
All selects all elements of the selected face.
Loop selects connected edges to the selected edge.
Shared selects UV elements that are separate in UV space but shared in 3D space.
Flip Horizontal flips the selected element horizontally.
Flip Vertical flips the selected element Vertically.
Flip Center flips the selected element both horizontally and vertically.
+90 rotates the selected element by 90 degrees clockwise.
-90 rotates the selected element by 90 degrees counterclockwise.
Auto aligns each element to the center.
Quad unfolds the UVs into a rectangular shape.
Boundary aligns the outer edges and sizes of the last selected elements.
The Left Tool in the UV Editor aligns selected UV elements to the left.
The Right tool in the UV Editor aligns selected UV elements to the right.
The Top Tool in the UV Editor is a tool that aligns selected UV elements upward.
The Center V tool in the UV Editor is a tool to align selected UV elements around a vertical center.
The Bottom Tool in the UV Editor aligns selected UV elements downward.
The Space H tool in the UV Editor is a tool that will horizontally align selected UV vertices to be equally spaced.
The Space V Tool in the UV Editor is a tool that will vertically align selected UV vertices to be equally spaced.
The sew tool attaches shared UV edges in the UV editor. Select shared edges or use the shared tool to select, and then use sew to merge them.
The move sew tool is similar but also moves connected elements when shared edges are merged. The weld tool merges UV vertices.
Weld to first merges to the position of the initially selected vertex.
Weld to center merges to the middle position of the selected vertices.
Weld to last merges to the position of the last selected vertex.
Detach tool separates selected faces from connected UV elements.
The arrange group function arranges UV elements uniformly in the texture space.
Pack places UVs in the texture space without overlapping and fills empty spaces.
Fit places already arranged UVs tightly in the texture space.

The export tool under misc exports the UV layout as an image file. The exported image can be used as a guideline for image editing in software like Photoshop or Paint. UV Editor For more detailed information, please check the following link Check

The Side Stair tool is a tool for generating stair-shaped meshes in a side step format.
The Side Stair Tool can create circular planes in two ways. Click-Drag to create, edit Create and edit using One Click Build

Select the Side Stair Tool. Click and drag the mouse on the scene to create a plane of the desired size. Once the plane is the desired size, click to finish creating the mesh. Adjust the properties of the Side Stair tool and select the element, or press another tool to finish. note You can continue fine-tuning with the Side Stair tool's properties until you select an element or press another tool to finalize.
